 <office:master-styles>
  <style:master-page style:name="Standard" style:page-layout-name="pm1" draw:style-name="dp1">
   <style:header>
    <text:p text:style-name="P1"><text:span text:style-name="T1">Svn $Revision: 61 $ <text:s text:c="3"/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">Page</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T1"> </text:span><text:page-number text:select-page="current">69</text:page-number></text:p>
   </style:header>
  </style:master-page>
  <style:master-page style:name="First_20_Page" style:display-name="First Page" style:page-layout-name="pm2" draw:style-name="dp1" style:next-style-name="Standard"/>
 </office:master-styles>
 <office:body>
  <office:text text:use-soft-page-breaks="true">
   <text:sequence-decls>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Illustration"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Table"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Text"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Drawing"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Figure"/>
   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:h text:style-name="P2" text:outline-level="4">Diary of George Parsons born 1890 Esquimalt Canada<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T3">1912</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3" loext:marker-style-name="T4">Please Note:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">{} </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">indicates clarification</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">(</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">?</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">) Word added but with some doubt as difficult to read</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">xxxx(?) </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">word of approximately” letters but unclear</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">Axxxcxx(?) </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">word probable letters and approx. number of letter but unclear</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">1/pxx </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">indicates diary number/page</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"><text:tab/>First down this the first day of the new year 1912 to commence a dairy I have I have never undertaken such a task before and have not the faintest idea how the thing should be done. I suppose that if I wanted to do it properly I should start with an account of my ancestors my parents and my past. Of the first however I know nothing of the second I do not intend to say anything here ; and of my past well I cannot undertake to write an autobiography in one night. Sufficient unto the day is the recounting thereof.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"><text:tab/>It was indeed been quite an eventful one. Perhaps though to give some description of my present position.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:tab/>I am now 2<text:span text:style-name="T9">nd</text:span> brewer to Messrs Campbell Praed and Co Wellingbourgh under Messrs <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">2 </text:span>Shake &amp; Briggs as first brewer &amp; Manager respectively I came here on Oct 1<text:span text:style-name="T9">st</text:span> of last year (1911) from a post of 3<text:span text:style-name="T9">rd</text:span> brewer a t Messrs of Wethered &amp; Sons Marlow, where I was getting £50 a year; that post I had held from May <text:s/>1911, it being the post I took after my pupillage under Mr B Patterson at the Swan Brewery, Fulham.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"><text:tab/>I was a pupil there from 1<text:span text:style-name="T9">st</text:span> March 1910 to April 1911 &amp; my father paid a premium of £100 a year for me. The amount paid (£150) covered a period of 18 months but the job at Marlow turned up, through my old friend Carl Wooten who held it moving to hancocks brewery, Cardiff , and I accepted it at the salary stated above with the promise of a rise to £70 at the end of 6 months.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"><text:tab/>The position however, was not a satisfactory one although I spent a very pleasant summer there, and when through Mr H Harman, consulting Brewer, I was offered the post here I <text:span text:style-name="T12">a</text:span>pplied for it.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:tab/>My first visit to this place was made the 18<text:span text:style-name="T9">th</text:span> July 1911, when I came down for an interview with one of the directors <text:s/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:span text:style-name="T13">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T14">3<text:line-break/></text:span>Mr Smith of Smith &amp; Co brewers, Oundle.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:tab/>It was made the day of the great railway strike, and a very hot day it was too. The strike however did not effect me, as I got up from a Marlow &amp; down here just as I had prevously planned.   I got back to London well also but returned to Marlow I had to walk from Maidenhead. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"><text:span text:style-name="T15"><text:tab/>I started work here on 1st Oct 1911 and set myself to acquire greater knowledge in the detail of brewery working &amp; more experience in the management of men. The former I found could be aquired thoroughly in this position; but the disinclination of the men to submit to authority and also i suppose my own want of tacht and firmness, made the <text:s/>latter more difficult than i had anti- cipated. So much so in fact that at the end of a month I appeared to have en-tirley lost their respect and to have made a hopeless mess of it. It moreover appeared that the men had been much <text:s/>troubled by a wild fellow who had held my position before I were afraid that I would </text:span>make myself objectionable like he did. By keeping very quite since, however, I seem to have regained there confidence &amp; respect and a slight but successful brush with one of the more antagonistic of them only last week has helped me somewhat. Today has also been a very favourable one I consider in this respect. Most aus-picipusly so I consider being the 1st of the New Year. I started at six by collecting a body of men to demolish an old slate fermentory vessel for we are at present constructing a new Fermenting Room but of that elsewhere. I thus had for the first time the direction of a body of men and although the operation was a delicate one I think I managed very well.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P12">Later in the day light , the “Engineer” was required to remove a mechanical <text:s/>rouser standing on th<text:span text:style-name="T12">ree</text:span> feet soldered to the bottom of a copper lined F.V. <text:s/>He was afraid to meddle with the copper <text:s/>&amp; prososed to saw through the legs and leave bits still  soldered to the bottom. I suggested however that the solder  should be melted by means of a blast lamp borrowed from the painters working close by. Mr Sprake was first received my plan coldly, but later encouraged me.&amp; I borrowed the lamp &amp; did the job quite successfully my-self; in spite of the pessimistic warnings of Hight as to danger of a blow lamps. In the evening i was much surprised to get a letter from Mr Baylis Allen of Burnley. He comes from a modest home, but is a student at the Royal College of Art, where he has been very <text:span text:style-name="T15">successful. My sister met him there first as a sort of pupil teacher I &amp; had a great deal to do with him. It now appears he considers himself in love with her &amp; draws pictures of a successful career. He has in fact proposed to her. I have never yet seen him but have endeavoured to stop the affair &amp; have succeeded in per-suading my sister to get him to put off the idea. I am sure my parents would be very much upset if they knew about it which they do not. Mr Allen now </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">wants to call upon me on his way back</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">. </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P13">Monday 1<text:span text:style-name="T9">st</text:span> Jan</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P12"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">6 </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">to the R.C.A, on Monday next its very annoying. I went round to see Mr Morris this evening he is head master of the all Saints parish school here &amp; I had an introduction to him from my Aunt Jennie Mrs D</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">o</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">wnar, who knows his family at Bulwell nr Nottingham I found him setting forth for a whist drive but Mrs Morris the mother of 4 children entertained me with conversation &amp; mince pies. Whether it was the affect of the latter or not I don’t know but I felt rather cheap before going to bed.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P14"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/3-Tuesday-2nd-Jan.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 2nd Jan</text:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/>Went down to the brewery at 9:30 &amp; spent the day supervising alterations &amp; bringing stock books up to date. Went to tea with Sprakes. I wrote to Mr Allen saying I would be pleased to see him to Lunch on Monday or could see him on Thurs 11th when I go to town for O.R dinner. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/4-Wednesday-3rd-Jan.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 3rd Jan</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Got to the brewery at 7.0. Wrote to Dorrie telling her about Allen. Have spent the rest of the day quietly suffering from a slight headache. I forgot to say yesterday I Went to the Palace to see the Delhi Dunbar pictures. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/5-Thursday-4th-Jan.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 4th Jan</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P17"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">7 </text:span>Got to the brewery at 9.30. Found there had been a fuss about the allowance Mr Briggs found a man drunk on Monday night &amp; took the opportunity to cut down the allowance by 1 pint to each man. This morning the men from the brewhouse claimed their pint before breakfast John Waples the forman refused to serve it &amp; Mr Sprake supported him.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P17">Abbot objected strongly &amp; said he must throw up his job. On making enquiries we found that the brewery men had been having 5 pints every day &amp; an extra pint for throwing out grains they ought only to have had 4, and as they are to be seduced by 1 pint they now only ought to have 3. They objected to loosing 2 pints a day. Mr Sprake &amp; I decided that they are to have 3 pints like everyone else on non-brewing days &amp; an extra pint on brewing days; also the man who throws out the grains is to have an extra pint.<text:line-break/>I wrote to Brous letting him of my decision not to go with him to Switzerland as he had proposed on account of the cost (£10) but suggested that <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">8 </text:span>he should go to Belg<text:span text:style-name="T12">iu</text:span>m with us. I went round to Mr Morris&apos; in the evening to return a book he had lent me &amp; there met Mr &amp; Mrs Paget. Stopped till 8:30 took two hands at bridge. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/8-Friday-5th-Jan.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 5th Jan</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Got to bry at 6:00 Just after Just after 7:30 I went down to the office, one of the clerkd ( Balaam ) was there but very busy. Under pretence of looking at morning paper I retired to sanctum near fire and took down phinketts calendar which Mr Walden the chief clerk had appropriated. I took it up to the brewing room &amp; concealed it in my desk to await developments. Went for a walk after dinner &amp; met Mr Terry, the vicar he invited me in after evensong next Sunday 7th I will go. At tea Sprake disclosed to me that he had reason to believe that the antagonism of the men towards me had been started by his predecessor Mr Davson. <text:line-break/>Went around to Mr Morris in evening &amp; played bridge till 12:00.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P18"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/52-Saturday-6th-Jan-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 6th Jan 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P17">Got to bry at 9.30 Sprake witnessed a scene of much excitement in office when Mr Waldon discovered the loss of his calendar. He was furious other clerks tried to calm him Sprake denied all knowledge. I <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">9 </text:span>approached Mr Briggs with regard to giving mineral waters for Choral Society dance Went for a walk round Doddington &amp; Wilby in afternoon but weather was damp &amp; miserable. In evening finished books of photos for JD Holland &amp; AV Greensteet my colleages at Marlow. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/7-Sunday-7th-Jan.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Sunday 7th Jan</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Attended Holy Communion at All Saints church a 8 am. Spent morning in rooms until 11:30. Went down to brewery took photo of stage of operations fermenting room Went for a short walk before returning to dinner which I took with Mrs Balaam, my landlady. Dozed in afternoon untill 3.00 when I went for a ealk down to the river Nene. Went to Evensong at All Saints for first time &amp; afterwards went on to the vicar&apos;s There I met a fellow named Rowbotham who is in a printing business ( Bellamys ) in the town. He is a member of the church lads brigade . He offered to introduce meto the Church Institute next Friday.<text:line-break/>Left about 10:30 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/51-Monday-8th-January-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 8th January 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19">Bry at 6.30 Worked on balancing stock After breakfast had curious incident with <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">10 </text:span>Mr Sprake On Saturday he had been faced with the necesity of brewing an AK.<text:line-break/>This is a light bitter beer of 16.0 bls &amp; closely resembles a light mild of which we have a good sale of 15.0lbs. The sales of AK are about 4 brls a week. We are now without a small vessel &amp; can brew nothing less than 45 brls. We have 3 60 brl versels available &amp; a 120brl vessel in the Room in which the alterations are being carried out. I was opposed to brewing in this. The beers that we had brew were a large mild (xxx), a xx &amp; the AK. I suggested that the large vessel should remain empty &amp; that we brewed 120bls 0f xxx &amp; 60 brls 0f xx the latter of &amp; lighter shade than usual so that part could be racked as AK &amp; the rest as xx <text:line-break/>Sprake would not listen to this but insisted in filling the large vessel xx two 60 brls with xxx &amp; the other vessel with 45 brls A.K. I therefore made arrangments for the workmen to leave the large vessel open to us.This morning Sprake was working <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">11</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>because he did to know what he could do with 45 brls of AK ie about 3 months supply. I said nothing of my previous plan &amp; we discussed the advisablity of selling it as xxx or red All at once Sprake declared he had hit on a splendid plan. This was to brew a xx of light colour ..etc ... ! Exactly my plan of Saturday This was adopted! Sprake had told me on sat of the affect on Walden of the loss of his calander before going to breakfast this morning I replaced it by a dimuative one cut from a pocket diary. I noticed it had been torn down when I went to the office this morning but Walden said nothing. Men arrived Adams to erect new vessels in a afternoon .<text:line-break/><text:tab/>Allan was to come to tea but after all arrangement had been made I got a telegram to say he had taken the wrong train &amp; had been carried right through to London. Terribly wet night snow fell &amp; turned to slush Studied the germination of barley corn Despatched photo&apos;s to Marlow. <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">12</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/10-Monday-15th-Jan-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 15th Jan 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:tab/>Its been a week It&apos;s a week since I have recorded any of my doing this laps has come very soon after the commencement of this diary but I have been having a very busy time </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T20"><text:tab/>T</text:span>uesday I rem<text:span text:style-name="T20">em</text:span>ber was wet then almost every day lately <text:span text:style-name="T20">has been </text:span>wet. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:tab/>Wednesday I went to the coral society practice. That afternoon I remember was fine and in the dinner hour I took my stand camera upto the Sprates with the idea of taking aphoto of little John. He was so terrified that at the site of me focusing it that we could not calm him afterwards and the expidention ended in failure.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>Thursday the 11th I got to the brewery early and did my book work. After breakfast I <text:soft-page-break/>changed &amp; caught the excursion train to london. Brought newt chemical analysis in the Charring Cross Rd and proceed to SK Dorrie met me with much effectioness in the museum <text:line-break/>Had lunch with her &amp; Grace &amp; Doyle Wyles in the common room &amp; afterwards had a smoke with a student named Emberon while Dorrie got her things on. Went up west with her. Bought soft felt hat at Dunns in Strand then walked up to British Museum where we met Allen who was supervising the work of students there. Found him deeply versed in all the lore of the exhibition &amp; very willing to scatter his information, Returned to S.K to tea with Wyleses &amp; Miss Eckersly After tea proceeded to Stansfield&apos;s Fulham. Found Paterson &amp; Dickenson there. Great changes had been made. Many men had been dismissed Pat&apos;s idea being to effect greater amalgamation &amp; co-operation amoung the departments.<text:line-break/>He himself had taken over the management of the offices 4 stables – the work that Mrs Murrey had done – and he had found plenty of room for improvments. Dickenson had been having horse exersize by riding a horse that had been laid up. Patterson went of to a dance. I stayed there to change left 6.15 Got up to S.K met Allen <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">14 </text:span>outside Common room he told me Dorrie had gone on to Victoria I followed. Got into Underg. Trains going wrong way got out at Glouster Road had to watch a num stop go through reached Victoria 6.45. Found Brous with Dorrie had a few words with her and then went of with Brows for O R Dinner, walked across park to “Monico” Found a gathering of 27. At our table we had M.J Misfan H Wallis G E.cllort and a Boorman KFD Waters Inman Mr KHW Knoose Myself with Brous next to meand opposite H G Yates soccer blue and Amatuer International , a master at the school. Had a quite evening but nice to see all the old friends. After dinner walking with Brous we met Gablins who was one of our succesful school fellows at the <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strand_School" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Strand school</text:a>.went to ch X with Brous then made for St Pancras catching the 12:15 home I got to bed about 2:45 <text:line-break/><text:tab/>Friday got to the Brewers at 9:30 Smith was there and Sir Hurbert Praed came on <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">5</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>Afterwards. They had full meeting &amp; passed a vote of thanks to Mr Sprake fo rthe satisfactory condition of things. <text:line-break/>In the evening we found much to our distress that john the foreman was drunk &amp; did not know what he was doing. Sprake was very troubled.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>Saturday we talked the matter over. John Waples had given way two or three times before but he had promised to keep straight &amp; nothing had been done. We agreed that we must make some change. Sprake said that Waples should be got away from spirit stores. Who could take his place ? King of the Bottling Store was the only man but how could he be spared. I suggested that he should be given charge of the both &amp; Mason the odd man should help him.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>This was agreed upon. King was willing if Waples did not mind. In evening john who had <text:span text:style-name="T20">had </text:span>a talking to from Sprake ea<text:span text:style-name="T20">rl</text:span>ier in the day and who had been told of new plan was s upset that he found he could not carry on his <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">6</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>work. He went to Sprake &amp; made a clean<text:line-break/>breast of it said that the temptation in the spirit room was too much for him &amp; he would be able to get on much better under new scheme. Thanked Sprake for his kindness &amp; consideration.<text:line-break/>Went for a walk but found roads very dirty Noticed suspicion of an approaching cold in stiffness etc &amp; sore throat.<text:line-break/>But I havent mentioned anything of friday night. There was a Conversation at the Technical Institute. Proceedings opened with a concert. Got there well before the beginning found Miss Gent sitting just inside the door. She is a great friend of Mrs Balaam&apos;s lives just opposite in fact fathers a prosperous builder. Just after I got here she had got me tickets for the Wellingboro&apos; Dramatic <text:soft-page-break/>Society&apos;s dance, I had not seen here before <text:line-break/>I went to this in all innocence thinking it a good opportunity for meeting some people. It was a poor affair Mrs Balaam introduced me to Miss G.<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>I found her not brilliant but seemed genuine &amp; unassuming. As she was leaving early I offered to see her home about 3 minutes walk. I did so &amp; returned to dance. Imagine my astonishment &amp; indignation , when a few days after I found that before the dance she had announced that she was “maching” me. Report substanciated by my conduct. <text:line-break/>Now I meet her again having only seen her once since that, in Mrs Balaam&apos;s. I had however met her brothers. I endeavoured to act as If nothing unusual had occurred &amp; sat down &amp; chatted to her until the arrival of Corly one of our clerks offered an opportunity of escape. Rowbotham also turned up &amp; I sat out the concert with him.<text:line-break/>At the dance I had two with her. One was Interval dance. Varying refreshments being in force I had not see any obligation to treat her especially as she had announced her intention of going home just afterwards &amp; so I did not offer. A spirit of parsimoniousness the result of my somewhat lavish expenditure <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>of the prevous day no doubt having much to do with it. But in any case I did not want to do anything to abtain favour in her eyes but rather the reverse as I heard she is always imagining herself in love with others &amp; they with her. Noticed attempts to get me to escort her &amp; her little sister home again but was not having any. Rowbotham who apparently understands the situation sharing in my amusement.<text:line-break/>Sunday I attended the service at 11 o&apos;clock at All Saints Church. This is a Choral Eucharist. The church was well filled but largely with school children &amp; those who had lately left school. The gospel &amp; epistle were chanted &amp; the vicar which sounded strange &amp; almost rediculous to my ears and he also chanted many other parts of the service which in no way enhanced it&apos;s impressivness in my opinion. <text:line-break/>The cread was sung only by the choir. This has always struck me as a particualrly reprehencable practice. 2 old poeple only <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">9</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>communicated, therefore the remainder of the congregation might just as well have spent the morning in their gardens. <text:line-break/>I went to dinner with the Sprakes, walked to finedon in the afternoon had tea with the Sprakes but left at 5:30 .<text:line-break/>Spent the evening with Mrs Balaam in her room. Mr Balaam dropped in with his daughter &amp; stayed some time.<text:line-break/>This morning Monday I got to the brewery at 6.30. Did my orders before breakfast &amp; other books after. Did not go down after dinner. Have spent the afternoon on the couch getting ready for the Brigg&apos;s dance to night. I have had a cold the last day or so I must have caught it on the train on the Thursday night. <text:line-break/>The Sprakes have given me some <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.oldandsold.com/articles35/common-cold-12.shtml" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Amm Quinine</text:a> I have been dosing myself with it. It appears to have had a good effect. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/49-Tuesday-16th-Jan-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Tuesday 16th Jan 1912</text:a></text:h>
