      </draw:image>
     </draw:frame></draw:a><text:line-break/>Miss Marjorie Edwards<text:line-break/>Roseland<text:line-break/>Hatton Park<text:line-break/>Wellingborough<text:line-break/>Taken probably approx 1960</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P21">Got to the dance at 8.0 just before the start I did not get away until 3.45.<text:line-break/>We all had a glorious time. The thing went well from the start. 24 dances &amp; 2 leap year <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">20</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>extras. Principal partner was Miss Edwards, I looked first found her out once more &amp; she asked me for the 2nd Leap year. This turned out to be unfortunate because when the dance came Miss Briggs herself whose coming out it was came up to me I had to refuse- very annoying. She looked splendid I had two dances with her &amp; she sat opposite at supper where she was quite jolly not so quiet &amp; retiring as she was at the dance at which I met her for the first time. I had two with her sister Dorothy &amp; we got on quite well.<text:line-break/>My supper partner was a Miss Fish who had lived in Lisbon all her life. She was there during the <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.fatima.org/essentials/opposed/masonrevol.asp" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">revolution</text:a> a very interesting My partner in the first leap year was Miss Frost a farmers daughter a jolly girl we had arranged it before. Miss Barnes who came from N Kensington &amp; was staying with the Briggs had two dances, small but very attractive very like May Buttnshaw who came home from China with us. Miss Corly was looking very pretty &amp; very saucy Miss Briggs however held her own easily. I got <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">21</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T22">v</text:span>ery tired before the close and very glad to get to bed. Got up about 9. this morning did not feal stiff found the cold had been banished by the terrible amount of sweating I had done - It was hot .<text:line-break/>But I did not feel by any means quite fit. Spent quiet day in the brewery. In the evening found the Cooper Thornhill asleep in front of the fire in his shop. He said he felt very bad &amp; was suffering from cold this though I did not believe it at the time proved to be true as he stayed away the next day. I am sorry I misjudged him. Mrs Balaam also suffereing from cold but cheerful the same.<text:line-break/>About 8.30 Rowbotham called to take me round to the church Institute. We played bridge with two excellent players &amp; I got hopelessly lost I made an awful show. I decided to join. They have three rooms. Card room, Reading Room, Billiard Room with a full sized table. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/12-Wednesday-17th-January.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 17th January</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P21">Got to the brewery at 6.30. mashed Spent quiet day . Weather wretched sleet was falling <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">22</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>When I walked down to brewery, afterwards turned to snow &amp; everything was white when I went home to breakfast. Sleet &amp; snow continued to fall all day: Paid dentist bill 35/ with father&apos;s cheque. I am going to the choral soc. Prach to night After much cogitation I wrote to thank Mrs Briggs as <text:soft-page-break/>follows:-<text:line-break/>I wish to thank you heartily for the extremly enjoyable time I spent at your dance last time I spent at your dance last Monday. Such a successful debut should augur well for the happiness of Miss Briggs in the future. The work which such a dance must necessarily entail, was I am sure amply rewarded by the thorough way in which everyone enjoyed themselves and I hope it has left you quite well. <text:line-break/>Made my way to Choral practice through the snow. The was quite a thick layer when I came back. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/50-Thursday-18th-Jan-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 18th Jan 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P21">Woke up to find that 6 or 7 inches of snow had fallen but a thaw was setting in. This is the first snow we have had <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">23</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>this winter. The long distance drays Kimbolton etc. had to abandon their journey their journey. Went to technical institute in the evening. Mr Enson the principal who is a mason informed me that Mr Sprake has decided to become one This is the first I have heard of a decision though he has spoken of his inclination in that direction. Ensor told me I ought to join being a member of such a strong masonic firm. Perhaps I will we will “Wait &amp; see “. Had tea with downing in the office. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/14-Friday-19th-Jan-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 19th Jan 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P22">Got in to mash at 6.0 felt very sleepy all day. T night is the Mens Supper We expect to see Mr S<text:span text:style-name="T23">m</text:span>ith there. We want to see him about floor of new fermenting room. When he was down here last friday unknown to me he discussed the question &amp; said that he thought we could sling the floor from the roof principlals In this brewery at Oundle I believe he has some such temporary scaffold arrangement. Sprake is not sufficiently practical to have ay views on the subject. Nothing was said to me &amp; nothing was done about it Sprake <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">24</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>I had previously decided that the whole question ought to wait until the vessels were in. The impatience of the carpenter Skeers however stirred up trouble. He went to Briggs to get his sanction to order the materials to carry out Mr Smiths idea. Briggs who quiding is that the directors are infallible thought that Mr Smiths scheme must be adopted &amp; told Sprake so. Sprake must be made no objection &amp; then came &amp; told me for the first time all about. I made a fuss because I believed that the best plan would be to build the floor to the level existing in the other rooms and work the vessels from the top of a moveable platform like that we had at Marlow. I had put forward this suggestion before I now elaborated it. Ridiculed Smiths idea also Sprake suggestion that the floor should be at a working level from the roof beams. Finally &amp; declared I would have nothing more to do with it. Sprake turned at once &amp; rushed off to <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">25</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>ask Briggs for a respite until Mr Smith could be again consulted. This was agreed to Sprake asked my if I would speak for him at the supper if he felt very stutter so I consented.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>Assembled in office at 7.15 &amp; went across to suppliers. The chief business was the election of a larger committee of the sick Benefit chief to deal with the alterations necessitated by the Insurance Bill.<text:line-break/>The attitude of the men should quite clearly that if they had heard anything about the bill they had not grasped they fact that it would affect them.<text:line-break/>The motion was put that the committee he enlarged but no one attempted to discuss it. Briggs tried to impress apose them that something ought to be done, but the only reponce he got was a suggestion from John Waples that the matter be allowed to stand over for another 12 months. Finally the men elected a represtative committe after Briggs had practically told them that they had got to. Mr Newman and <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">26</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span>Mr Woodhams two pro&apos;s sang two songs each the former comic the <text:soft-page-break/>latter &quot;descriptive&quot; Abbot then proposed a “Vote of thanks to the Directors and Brewery Office staff coupled with the names of the chairman &amp; Mr Sprake “. Sprake called I rose with Mr Briggs. He made a speech. I had to follow I felt very trembly &amp; shuffled my feet My brain seemed to have left me. I pulled myself together. I can&apos;t remember what I said but I believe it was as follows. <text:span text:style-name="T24">Mr Chairman &amp; gentlemen I have much pleasure in thanking you on behalf of Mr Sprake &amp; myself <text:s/>for your vote of thanks. I have nothing of importance to say to you for Mr Briggs has already said everything much more ably than I could say it myself. I can however say that it has given us the greatest pleasure to be with you tonight and I think that thsat is in itself a indication of the great good felling which exists between us and the men -.-.-. </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T26"> I again thankyou very much for your vote of thanks”</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P22"><text:span text:style-name="T25"><text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">ask Briggs for a respite until Mr Smith could be agn consulted. This was agreed to Sprake asked me if I would </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">speak for him at the supper if he felt very stuttery so <text:s/>consented.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:tab/>Assembled in office at 7:15 &amp; went across to the supplier. The chief business was the election of a larger committee of the sick Benefit club to deal with the altercations necessitated by the Insurance Bill</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:tab/>The attitude of the men showed quite clearly that of they had heard anythng about the bill they had not grasped they fact that us would affect them<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T30"> </text:span>We adjouned to the office for a W7S &amp; then home through the rain.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/15-Saturday-20th.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 20th</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>No evil effects from the dinner. Walked to wilby in the afternoon. Went around to the Morrises in the evening met Mr Hill, Mrs Morris&apos;s brother a very nice chap. Played bridge for an hour. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/16-Sunday-21st.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 21st</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>Went to the parish church at 11 Vicar preached as usual condeming the service of morning prayer. Had dinner at Mrs Balaam slept all afternoon; wrote to Popsy Cupper in evening. also to father telling him about supper and to Dorrie about the dance. Told her if she would not go out with me she would be able to go out much more. With regards to Allan afair Said latter had no right to think about such things &amp; ascribed his folly to the influence of the collage. If she was going to think any more about it she must tell father. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/17-Monday-22nd.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 22nd</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>Bry @ 7.0 Uneventfull day Foggy &amp; cold Went down to office to tea where they were not at all pleased to see me apparently. Had a pleasant evening at home. chemistry. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P24" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T24">Tuesday</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/19-Wednesday-24th.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"> 2<text:span text:style-name="T24">3</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T24">rd</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P25"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T24">Got up at 8:0 to find more snow but a rain falling. By at 9:30 had to brew with 2 men Beford &amp; jolly in brewhouse Abbot being away Tech in evening X Rays demonstration </text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/19-Wednesday-24th.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 24th</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>Bry at 6:30 Uneventfull day <text:span text:style-name="T24">In evening went to Warwich’s to be measured for new summer suit. Read in evening until 8:10 When I went t Choral Soc Practice.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P26" text:outline-level="4"><text:soft-page-break/>24th January 1912</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 Very mild. chorus in evening. Saw Margorie in evening but she was with her cousin. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">30 </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T30">several questions </text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P27" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T24">Friday </text:span>2<text:span text:style-name="T24">6</text:span>th January 1912</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P28"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T24">Bry at 6:00. In morning had discussions with Mr Briggs &amp; Sprake about the in fermenting from the beams at the old level under the roof </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">3</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P29">unexpectedly &amp; thy were thrown off &amp; one of them sprained his ankle Choral practice in evening</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/27-Thursday-1st-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 1st Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Worked on Stock books. Mr Biggs asked me again if I would take Miss Briggs skating so I called at house at 2.15 and found Mr &amp; Mrs Bready. The ice was rather soft as it was thawing and there were many cracks and bumps Mrss Briggs could now go quite nicely but the ankle was again a drawback. Returned to tea these - very pleasant. Before I went home I interviewed Skeers and his explanation of the misunderstanding was that he took my words as instruction &amp; did not know whose plan to follow. I pointed out to him that I was in no position to give anyt directions. changed and went into Mrs Balaams to play wist there was a party of eight including Mr &amp; Mrs Moins we had a very good evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/28-Friday-2nd-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 2nd Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Mashed Worked on stock books Mr Smith came down. I offered to take Miss Briggs skating. Much colder day </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">3</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">9 </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T31">and inclined to snow. We had much trouble with Miss</text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/29-Saturday-3rd-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 3rd Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P22">Very cold still. Bry at 10.0. In afternoon went skating again near Findon Road.<text:line-break/>had good afternoon sport skating for nearly 3 hours. I helped Mrs Briggs for some time while she tried &amp; she got on very well. Sprake turned up afterwards &amp; Ms &amp; Mrs Morris Miss Briggs went by herself a bit and towards the end we had several splendid runs together. I went alone a good bit and <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">40 </text:span>felt much more at home. Feel got very cold so did Miss Briggs so we went for a run together that &amp; the walk home put them right again. Went to Briggs to tea Corly left after tea &amp; Mr Briggs went back to his work. I stayed &amp; played bagetelle for the first time; just beggining to get a + score when Miss Briggs finished Very cold night. Bry at 9.0. Read in paper to-day of shocking accident to submarine A3 sunk with 14 men this on the eve of Kings return from his successful Indian visit. His return has thus been marred by two sad events, the death of the Duke of Fife in Egypt &amp; this terrible accident. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/30-Sunday-4th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 4th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Glorious morning but still very cold indeed. Keen N.E wind church at 11. Bry after. Dinner with Mrs Baton in my room. Readd &amp; slewpt. Walk by the river. Flooded meadows freezing hard River frozen night across in places &amp; fringe of ice 4 - 6 ft broad along sides. Very keen wind. Sprakes for tea. Left at <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25"> </text:span>6.0. Return to rooms to write. Wrote long letters to father &amp; Dorrie 1st telling of amalgamation with Roubotham. Second of skating dances etc. Bry at 9.0. Dorrie&apos;s posted the sun. evening Fathers enclosing M.O For £2 not until Mon evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/31-Monday-5th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Monday 5th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Very cold morning thermometer I put outside retired into bulb at 25deg very keen N.E. to E wind all day. Went skating by river in afternoon with Miss Briggs &amp; Eileen Kelly. very cold wind which drove Miss Briggs home leaving me alone with girls. Spent most of the time falling over trying to help Eileen Kelly. Ice very smooth hard. Had short run with them to tea left at 5:45 Developed Photographs . Had new suite tried on. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/32-Tuesday-6th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 6th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 Cold morning changing after rain &amp; then warmer. Thawing all evening Tech 7 - 9. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/33-Wednesday-7th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 7th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Still thawing S.W wind during day snow &amp; ice rapidly disappearing. Evening on organic Chem. Choral practice. Walk round 3 mile spin in afternoon - very muddy </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/34-Thursday-8th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 8th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Bry at 7.0. Very warm all day. Letters from <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">2 </text:span>father with S.E.R. draftfor £3.18. wants me to go home. Must wait until March 2nd.<text:line-break/>Rain falling all day St Johns Ambulance Wist drive &amp; dance in evening. Went to thing Went in blue serge suit &amp; found myself one of the few not in evening dress. Nice dance after Wist drive. I scored 165 in 24 games Winner 184. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/35-Friday-9th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 9th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Tech in evening . Briggs bought Mr Bearn up &amp; took him round the bry. Walden accompanied them. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/36-Saturday-10th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 10th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 Went for a walk with Sprake in afternoon &amp; returned with him to Briggs to tea wore light brown suit for feast time. Miss Colleck there played bagatelle till 9.0 - supper then Miss Briggs played a bit </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/37-Sunday-11th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 11th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Early service at 8.0. church at 11.0. short stroll with Sprake &amp; Briggs to lunch Walked to Wilby after &amp; took Sprake back to rooms to spend evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/38-Monday-12th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 12th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7.0 Sprake is invited as a mason to night. Spent evening in my room. young Bearne came in about 8.0 asked me to go around &amp; spend evening some time. Must leave it till next weak but thing it is very good indeed of them. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/21-Tuesday-13th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 13th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">3 </text:span>Bry at 6:0 to mash. Weather dull and wet and rather colder. Tech in evening . Got a letter from Dorrie telling me she had been staying in town with Mrs Eclersley Tech in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/22-Wednesday-14th.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 14th</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7:0 walk with Sprake in afternoon. Mrs de Martin,s dance in evening. Only a few present great excess of girls but I had a good time. Danced cheifly with Miss, Frost Corly Edwards 2 with Madge Briggs. Took Miss Corly home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/23-Thursday-15th-February.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 15th February</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Up at 9.0 very tired. Slack day Tech in evening </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/24-Friday-16th.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 16th</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:30 Mr Smith came down. Had argument with Sprake about new Unicorne He condembed his weakness in allowing Briggs to send it out when it had only been in bottle for 4 days. Went to <text:soft-page-break/>ladies Hockey Chib Wist drive and dance in Masonic hall in evening. Very hot danced with Miss Smith the good looking assistant to Thompson the dentist . </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/25-Saturday-17th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 17th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Bry at 10.0 Lunch at 1:30 with Rowthbottom for the first time. Short walk in afternoon, dressed and went to Briggs for tea. Dorothy at home and Mrs Barnes from Kensington also Eileen Kelley. Went to Mrs de Mastin&apos;s dancing class afterwards; had reverse &amp; Borton demonstrated Spake went down to Wotton-under-Edge for 10 days <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">4 </text:span>to me for the first time. Played bagatelle in the evening did not leave till nearly 11.0 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/26-Sunday-18th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 18th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Briggs to dinner, went up to the garden afterwards with the girls then left them. Went for a walk knowing that they would be glad to be rid of me as Madge at any rate was very tired went back to tea &amp; stayed to supper. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/39-Monday-19th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 19th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Had busy morning. took Mrs Briggs Madge &amp; Miss Barnes over the brewery. Tea in office. Went in evening to entertainment given by Mr Morris children. Tiny little tots sang &amp; performed and then the bigger ones much struck by self passion of one of the girls in latter who acted well &amp; sang well too. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/40-Tuesday-20th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 20th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0. Bad cold developing kept myself warm all morning. Tea in office In evening went to Church History Lecture. Wrote to Dorrie &amp; Green street </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/41-Wednesday-21st-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 21st Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 7.30. Cold improving. Walked round 3 mile spin in afternoon. Choral S in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/42-Thursday-22st-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 22st Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 7.30. Miserably wet day. No T class in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/43-Friday-23rd-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 23rd Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Bry at 6.0. Got letter from Poppy. Tech in evening<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">5 </text:span>Afterwards went to The Three Musketeers at the Palace. Very good show. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/44-Saturday-24th-Feb-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 24th Feb 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.15. Refused invitation to go to dancing class with the Briggs. Went for walk. 3 mile spin with Rowbotham, then continued through Ditchford Went to Morris in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/45-Sunday-25th-February.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Sunday 25th February</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11,.0. Mr Smeaton exhorted us to go to confesion. Dinner with Mrs Balaam. Short walk with Rowbotham in afternoon Morris to tea &amp; stayed the evening. Had discussion on new High Church propoganda. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/46-Monday-26th-February.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 26th February</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.30. Letter from Dorrie Repleid &amp; wrote to Dickinson telling of my proposed journey home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/47-Tuesay-27th-February.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesay 27th February</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">Bry @ 6.0 Letter from father. He seemed annoyed because he thought Dorrie was bent on going to a matinee on Sat &amp; he did not want her to. He had told heer to write me to see Dickinson on sat &amp; he thought she had not done so. I sent her card back from him to see. Sprake came back in afternoon. Mrs Briggs asked me in for sat Dorothy &amp; two friends there for half term. Had to refuse. Tech in evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31"><text:s/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/48-Wednesday-28th-February.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 28th February</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 7.0 Overhauling bycle all day Choral in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/53-Thursday-29th-February-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 29th February 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">6 </text:span>Bry at 6.30. Sprake came to lunch. In evengfinwe went to the licensed Victuallers dinner at <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.thehind.co.uk/" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">the Hind Hotel</text:a>. Briggs could not be present being down with Influenza. Had very good time. Bry contingent sat together &amp; firm paid for drinks. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/54-Friday-1st-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 1st March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Finished off bicycle. In evening went into Mr Bearns &amp; played whist. Had very nice evening. Genial &amp; homely family. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/55-Saturday-2nd-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 2nd March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 6.30. Left 11.15 Lunch caught 12.10 train to town. Met Dorrie at St Pancras Train to High Str Kensington, met Allan &amp; Miss Wyles at Olympia Saw <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.vam.ac.uk/content/articles/t/theatrical-revue/" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">the Miracle</text:a> Wonderful spectacle Will surely be the first of many shows of its kind. Common room to tea changed for dance at Stansfields, saw Wickins there. Had very good time at dance; Brous &amp; D there. Took Taxi to Victoria caught 12.0 midnight home. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/56-Sunday-3rd-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 3rd March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Early service at Cathedral &amp; 10.30 service Found father rather more cheerfull than usual. Trouble about letting Medway Villa house to Lent Oppenheim had woken him up. Dorrie looked far from well. She seems to be overworking herself and thinking much too much about Allen &amp; her own unmarried state Brous came in in the evening &amp; we had some music. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/57-Monday-4th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Monday 4th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">7 </text:span>Miserable day Wet &amp; blowing a gale. Had to say in doors all day. Dorrie came down early Brous looked in. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/58-Tuesday-5th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 5th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Another wretched day could not go out. Left after dinner by 1.45 train. Train service on S.E &amp; C.R completly altered owing to Coal Strike ( This started last Friday ). Had tea with Dorrie. Then went down to Fulham. Saw Dickinson &amp; stayed till 6.0. Bottling store underneath had been rearranged &amp; Mineral Water depart much enlarged. Saw g.g a he enquied after Dorrie. Saw Dorrie off at Victoria Impressed upon her the necessity for looking after herself &amp; not thinking so much about Allen also told her to do what she could to make things less dull at home. Caught 8.40 train at St P. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/59-Wednesday-6th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 6th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.30 Everything as usual Choral in evening 1st practice with band. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/61-Thursday-7th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 7th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery @ 6.15. Sprake came to lunch and we had a walk afterwards. Tech in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/60-Friday-8th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 8th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 9.30. Tech in evening otherwise uneventfull. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/62-Saturday-9th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 9th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Brewery at 6.30. Went for walk in afternoon with Sprake and visited one of our pubs at Mears <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">8 </text:span>Ashby; incognito so to speak called for Pat Sprake pronounced it very good beer &amp; the tenant heartily agreed with him. Sprake stopped to tea &amp; supper. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/63-Sunday-10th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 10th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Very good sermon from Mr Smeaton on the fall of David. Another walk with Sprake &amp; Rowbotham in afternoon &amp; Sprake came back to tea &amp; supper. Went to evening of service at All Saints. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/64-Monday-11th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 11th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.15. Uneventful day. Much suprised in evening to get a letter from Leonard Wallis telling me he had just taken up a job at Bedford. Funny that he should have come so close. I also have an invitation for a dance at Bedford so perhaps I shall go. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/65-Tuesday-12th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 12th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Sprake went to Leister in afternoon to meet Mrs Sprake. Tech in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/66-Wednesday-13th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Wednesday 13th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Bry at 9.30 First brew in New Tun Room Stout in the new 35 brl vessel. I suggested that Miss Briggs should come up and pitch it. Mr Briggs was delighted with the suggestion so they came up at 3.0. I showed them the wot coming down over the frig &amp; then took them to the new F.R explained the pitching of yeast &amp; asked Miss Briggs <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">9 </text:span>to throw in the first bowl full which she did &amp; so started the first fermentation in the new fermenting room amid loud applause. Went into tea afterwards Mrs Sprakes came down to tea in the brewing room. Choral practice in evening in spite of very bad throat. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/67-Friday-14th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 14th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7.0. Bad throat turning to cold in the head. Got a letter from Wallis in evening saying he would like to go to dance but asked me to buy his ticket. Must think what to do. Tech in evening &amp; went to Palace after to see “<text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.movs.eu/Film/The_AlaskaSiberian_Expedition-55503.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Siberia</text:a>” not very good. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/68-Saturday-15th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 15th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Saw Corly about Bedford dance he is not going &amp; does not know anyone who is. So I have decided not to go. Very bad cold in the head all day smoked cigarettes drank stout &amp; kept warm. Got a letter from Dorrie enclosing two fine photos of the design school. Stayed in evening. Wrote to Wallis telling him dance must be abandonded &amp; adising him to come over on Sun 24: Note to Mrs deMartin. Also wrote to Mother. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/69-Sunday-16th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 16th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Bry at 9.30. In afternoon went to lecture on Choral Singing &amp; choir training Gdr Davies <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">50 </text:span>Organist of Temple Church London. Very good speaker. Read all the evening <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fifteen_Decisive_Battles_of_the_World" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Creasy&apos;s 15 decisive battles of the world</text:a>. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/70-Sunday-17th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 17th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Very bad morning Went to Morris for tea Mrs Morris sister there, 15 but a fine girl. Mrs Morris not well children down with hooping cough; they do have rotten luck in that family ! </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/71-Monday-18th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 18th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 6.0. Stopped after breakfast only until 11. Then as my cold was bad. I went for a long walk through Doddington &amp; Wilby &amp; straight home. Did not go out again P<text:span text:style-name="T33">l</text:span>ayed cards with Mrs Balaam &amp; Miss Humphrey in evening &amp; tried to teach them bridge. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/72-Tuesday-19th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 19th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Cold still bad Went round 3 mile spin before dinner. Mrs Sprake dropped into tea. Spent evening taking &amp; developing a photo of the New Fermenting Room Wrote to Dorrie. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/73-Wednesday-20th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Wednesday 20th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 Cold improving. Spent greater part of the morning assisting in the bottling stores as two lads have been stood off. Mr Brigss not content with our little cermony of last Wednesday gave the men a cold lunch to day in honour of the new vessels </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/74-Thursday-21st-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 21st March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:span text:style-name="T33"><text:tab/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">51 </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T33">B</text:span>ry at 9:30. Spent morning guaging No5 Tech in evening. Cold devloping toothache. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/75-Friday-22nd-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 22nd March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry in evening. Cold worse &amp; toothache also I am waiting to see the morning papers &amp; the result of the division on the bill to settle the Coal Strike. It appears that the minors although they prevously refused to accept the bill have now climbed down and is the labour MP supported ir. The Unionists however opposed it but were beaton on the division. Evening at home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/76-Saturday-23nd-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 23nd March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:30 Goverment have postponed bill hoping that dispute will be settled at a conferance on Monday. Took Rowbotham round brewery in afternoon then back to change for Briggs. Got down there at 4:30 </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/77-Sunday-24th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 24th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">church at 11.0. Slept all afternoon found that dance had done the cold much good. Went to Sprakes to tea &amp; stopped the evening . Bry at 9.0. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/78-Monday-25th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 25th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.45. Stock came right out. Working on summary book rest of the day. Found Sprake had made a lot of mistakes in it. Much to my annoyance. I wish he would leave it to me But he he is so very keen on doing everything himself. Like this morning I found jelly painting a very dirty piece of metal &amp; told him he ought to wash it first with soda or potash just then Sprake came &amp; told him he must scrape it. There was no necessity for him to intefere he only mde me look a fool. Got a letter from father saying Dorrie was better. Spent evening reading <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.amazon.com/Soprano-Portrait-F-Marion-Crawford/dp/1116227975" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Marion Crawford&apos;s Soprano</text:a>. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/79-Tuesday-26th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 26th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 9.30. Mrs Briggs asked me to go in there on Sat as Madge was so dull said I was <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">53 </text:span>going to Bedford on that day but was compelled to accept for Friday. Find Corly who is also to be invited cannot come then &amp; don&apos;t know what will happen. It is becoming quite evident that they do not intend to leave me alone. If you see a good thing stick to it seems to be their idea. What their intentions are of course I cannot tell if they took upon me as a future son in law I am afraid they are wasting their hospitality. Madge is undoubtly a very nice girl and she would be much better if removed from the apparently over exacting care of her father and some artificial influence of her mother; but she does not seem to have that grasp of things pratical, that I should so certainly look for in an ideal wife. Of course I do not know enough about her to be sure that she is not sufficiently <text:soft-page-break/>domesticated. On the other hand it may be that they feel she ought to mix more with others, as she undoubtedly leads a very monotonous existence at present, her sister being away and having practically no friends of her own age and as far as I know no men aquaintances <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">54</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>In these circumstances they may possibilty look upon me as a safe person to help in her social education. I am beginning to think that my present plan would be to behave as if this were the case and treat her as much as possible like a near relation, with the least amount of that affectation and artificiallity with which it so customary to treat young ladies. If I can manage to do this with some success all may yet be well. <text:line-break/>The goverment is now making iteself rediculous over the coal strike. The conference did not take place yesterday the miners want a definite universal minimum wage of 5s for men &amp; 20 for the boys employed underground Asquith won&apos;t do this. The Daily Mail gives an excellent summary of the strike to day. <text:line-break/>To all appearances the situation stands precisly where it did on the first day of the strike &quot; but I think I will give the the article itself </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/80-Wednesday-27th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 27th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7.0 Mr Askwith had to confess yesterday that his efforts to end the strike by consent have failed the men still remain stubborn and so the goverment bill is to be proceeded with. Meanwhile large numbers of men are going back to work of their own accord. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/82-Friday-29th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 29th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0. Mr Smith came over &amp; Mr Briant &amp; Sir Herbert came down. Briant insisted that a new copper was necessary &amp; they are going to have one. Went into Briggs to tea Miss Coullech was there &amp; Corly. Played bagatelle all the evening. Miss Briggs dropped much of timidity and at times was quite coquettish not to say saucy. She was in fact more charming that I had ever seen her before. Had supper &amp; did not leave till 11.0.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/83-Saturday-30th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 30th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 9.15 got bike ready for ride to bedford. Started at 1.30 after many delays <text:line-break/>&amp; reached wallis digs at 3.5 <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">57</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>thanks to a stifish NW wind Found him somewhat improved but very impoverished &amp; working half time owing to coal strike. Went to Bedford school sports came back by train. Oxford &amp; cambridge boat race was to be held to day A gale of wind was blowing which entirly upset the C crew &amp; after vainly struggling over 1/2 the course but the umpire declared the race off. Rotten luck on Bourne, who if he had stroked the O boat to victory, would have been successful for the fourth time.<text:line-break/>It appears that the umpire declared the race off because the crowd helped the oxford crew &amp; they are going to row again on Monday.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/84-Sunday-31th-March-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 31th March 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Corly joined me. Had a long recitation of bathos from the curate who at 20 to one started the Liturgy so we came out. Short walk with Rowbatham in afternoon had tea alone with Mrs Balaam </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/85-Monday-1st-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Monday 1st April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">58</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Brewery at 6.30. They rowed the boat race again to day Oxford equiped their boat with a weather board 7in broad lashed to the riggers and had two football holders under each side the won the toss again &amp; as the wind was again very stronger, stronger than Saturday they chose the Middlesex station again. Neither boats sank this time, but the bad weather told very much in Oxford,s favour and they eventually won by a distance which was officially given as 6 lengths. The critics said they would have won what ever station they had had. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/86-Tuesday-2nd-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 2nd April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 Passed a very uninteresting day and there is nothing in particular to record. Read A comedy of errors in evening have started using a fountain pen again.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/87-Wednesday-3nd-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 3nd April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 6.0 Pestered all the evening by people who declared I had promised to buy from them tickets for the Amateur performance of the Gondoliers Finaly rushed of to the Morris &amp; bought one from him.<text:line-break/>His children still have the hooping cough very badly and to add to their worries their <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">59</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>servant apparently took it into her head to have a night out. I went with Mr Morris in an unsuccessful search for her.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/89-Thursday-4th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 4th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:30. Left for bedford at 3:35 Had arranged to pick up Wallis there but when I reached his rooms found he had gone. Reached St Pancras 6:10 Dorrie was to have met me here but she did not get up till about 6:30 &amp; I had gone onto holborn. Had a hurried tea &amp; caught the 6.55 changed at HH into an already crowded train. Squashed into guards van. Found a comfortable seat till swanly where the rest of the party got out (there were about 12 others ) and completed the journey in the guards seat. Dorrie came down by the next train. She had a nasty cold, otherwise all well at home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/90-Friday-5th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 5th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Spent qiuet day at home . Brous was away at Dover. May Gardener dropped in in the evening. She was very smart . I took her home afterwards &amp; saw Mr &amp; Mrs Gardener.<text:line-break/>During lent this year I got out of the habit of sugar in tea </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/91-Saturday-6th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 6th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">60</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Went over to Gillingham to get a pair of trousers from Cooper. Aunt Alice came down in afternoon &amp; Aunt Emily later.<text:line-break/>Mathews came in &amp; we played tennis all the afternoon &amp; got very tired.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/92-Sunday-7th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 7th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">church at 8.0 with Aunt Alice &amp; Emily; had to sit right up in the front .<text:line-break/>Went for a good walk with father in the evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/93-Monday-8th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 8th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Another quite day at home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/94-Tuesday-9th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 9th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Aunt alice had a telegram from lucion asking her to return to clapham as his wife alice was ill so she went up with dorrie &amp; I by the 1.52. We were very late . Dorrie &amp; I left here at Hh<text:line-break/>I went &amp; saw Brous at his office &amp; arranged to meet later at Picadily Circus and Dorrie went shopping while I deposited bags at St Panc. We all met at P.C &amp; went &amp; had tea. Wandered about till 6:45 when we took up our stand at the Royalty theatre for &quot;Milestones&quot; This is a play in three acts which <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">61</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>has been most excellently received. The act represents three different periods 1860, 1885, &amp; 1912. John Read appears in the first act as a young man. He makes money by realising the future of iron in shipbuilding and in 1885 appears as a prosperous middle aged man about to be knighted. In the last act he is of course very old. The play traces his changed from an enthusiastic reformer to a strong conservative also the change of a pushing young socialist to a labour MP who realises that the accomplishment of the milenium is as far off as ever &amp; will always continue to be so. It also lays stress on the self reliance of the rising generation as compared with that of the other two periods.<text:line-break/>We caught the 12.15 down &amp; got home to Wellingbourgh at 2.0.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/102-Wednesday-10th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 10th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 10.0 Took Dorrie into Briggs in afternoon Mrs Briggs was unfortunatly down with a bad cold The girls took us up to the garden. They had a Mrs Taylor from <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">62</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Wolverhampton with them a very nice girl. They asked Dorrie in for tommorow.<text:line-break/>We went on from there to the Morris &amp; met there Mr Churchill who keeps an antique shop in town. He took Dorrie home while I went to the choral practice.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/95-Thursday11th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday11th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30 Went up to rooms for Dorrie at 11.0 to take her out. Directly I had got in Miss B. &amp; Miss Taylor came along to take her up to the garden, but we explained and she went with me to look at the church &amp; we went for a walk down by the river afterwards. In the afternoon I went into the brewery but she went to the Briggs for tennis. I went up there later &amp; we went down to the house to tea &amp; stayed the evening. Dorrie, who did not seem at all taken with the family yesterday liked them better today. Which is only what I expected as I told her that they improve on aquaintance Got home about 11:30. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/96-Friday12th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday12th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 6.0 Yesterday Asquith introduced his Home Rule Bill (3rd) into <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">63</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T34">th</text:span>e house of commons He made a good speech explaining it to the House. Ireland is to have a Parliament consisting of a House of Commons of 164 and a senate of 40 appointed in the first instance by the home goverment &amp; afterwards by the Irish parliament. As regards finance it means that Great Britain gives Ireland <text:soft-page-break/>£2,000,000 and has no say as to the spending of it.<text:line-break/>It appears that Ireland at present costs us about £2,000,000 but the spending of this money is in the hands of the representitives of the whole nation. The tone of Mr Aquith,s speech was. What can be against the bill? He pointed out the advantage that it would bring about. Sir Edward Carson who replied felt that the goverment had only bought the bill in because the Irish members held the balance of parties &amp; forced them to. He also argued that the safeguards imposed on the Irish Parliament were useless.<text:line-break/>Went for a ride with Dories visiting churches Findon, Irthingborough, &amp; Rushden. Went <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">64</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>With Sprakes in evening to the Palace &amp; back there to supper.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/97-Saturday-13th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 13th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30. Rode over to Northhampton in afternoon accompanied most of the way by Miss Read. Visited the churches &amp; Eleanors cross at Hardington. This is a splendid monument in excellent preservation but shows the hand of the vandal in the initials scratched on the lower part. Asked by Miss Briggs to dinner tommorow but had to refusr as we had promised the Morrises. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/98-Sunday-14th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 14th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 sat next to Corby. In the brewery afterwards we met the Sprakes people who are staying with him. They do not look at all opulant though they are I beleive. Went to Morris to tea, the children still have the hooping cough &amp; Mrs Morris in Particular is very worried. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/99-Monday-15th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 15th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Sprake has gone of to his brothers wedding at newport pagnell. Dorrie went into the Briggs in the afternoon and went upto the garden for tea &amp; tennis meeting Miss Coulbeck. Briggs <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">65</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>got 5 tickets for the W.A.O&apos;s dress rehersal of The Gondaliers and I went with the 4 girls we enjoyed it immensely.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/100-Tuesday-16th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 16th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 We received this morning the news that the White Star Liner Titanic struck an Iceberg off the coast of Newfoundland at 10:20 on Sunday night and it reported that she has sunk though nothing definite is known. It was her Maiden voyage and she was the most luxuroius as well as the largest vessel afloat. This news devastated the Home Rule debate which was continued &amp; Mr Balfour in a very able speech yesterday. Went out for a good walk with Dorrie as we both had colds. She left by the 3.8 train. On the way to the station the Briggs picked us up with the brougham as they were going up to town by the same train. They are going on from there to Calais of course Dorrie went up with them. I came back with Briggs.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/101-Wednesday17th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday17th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 6.30. The sad news was confirmed that the Titanic had indeed sunk with with <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">66</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>about 1490 persons abroad. About 800 were saved ( mostly women ) by a liner which hurried to the scene on receiving distress signals by wireless. No details are yet known. The home rule bill passed it&apos;s first reading with a majority of 94 after a debate in the course of which Lord Robert Cecil aptly said that it reduced Ireland from the status of a wife to that of a mistress. Weighed myself stripped this <text:soft-page-break/>evening found my weight was 10 6 1/4 which is an increase of about 1/2 stone since I was rowing last summer. There was an eclipse of the sun to-day .91 of the whole was covered We saw it splendidly. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/103-Thursday18th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday18th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Went to performance at Electric thearter in evening rotten </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/104-Friday-19th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 19th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 to mash. Tech in evening Both yesterday and to-day have been glorious days and it has been just like summer. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/105-Saturday-20th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 20th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 9.30 feeling very wild with Sprake because he agreed to carry out an <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">67</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T34">i</text:span>dea of mine in the fermenting room &amp; did not do so. I told him I was tired of being played with in that way. He has over &amp; over again listened to my ideas with great apparent interest &amp; expressed his rediness to adopt then &amp; has done nothing further in the matter.<text:line-break/>went for a ride in afternoon to Pytchley &amp; Isham the churches in these villages both have traces of Norman work &amp; Pythchley is particuallarly interesting. Went to the amatuar performance of the Gondaliers in the evening. It was splendid : everyone went at it with splendid vigour and received a tremendous amount of encourament from the audience</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/106-Sunday-21th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 21th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 spent a quiet day wrote to father &amp; Dorrie in the evening </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/107-Monday-22th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 22th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">68</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Bry at 6.15 Mashed. Another beautiful day making the 5th in sucession </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/108-Tuesday-23rd-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 23rd April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>Bry at 9:30 fine day again wrote to Mr Holland about fire &amp; steam coppers. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/109-Wednesday-24th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 24th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:15 Another beautiful day went to choral soc practice in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/110-Thursday-25th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 25th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">bry at 9:30 day cold &amp; dull at first but brightened up later. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/111-Friday-26th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 26th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 another cold day. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/112-Saturday-27th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 27th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 started at 2.30 to meet Wallis at Kimbolton. Found I had a stiff NE wind to fight against met him this side of town. Very quite old fashioned place with castle gates opening on main street. Very fine park seat of Duke of Manchester. Had tea at old fashioned inn. Rode with wallis to Bletsoe &amp; back from there doing 40 miles in all. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/113-Sunday-28th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Sunday 28th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 collection for the destitute of the Titanic. Sprakes to tea. Unfortunatly because Miss Humphrey had Marjorie Edwards in to tea with her &amp; I missed what would have been for me a very nice party I was very sick with it. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/114-Monday-29th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 29th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 cold morning sprake went up to town to see Brant. Slight rain in afternoon </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/115-Tuesday-30th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 30th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">69</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Bry at 9.30 fine day but cold I spent most of the day trying to get hold of some organic chemistry for the exam on friday it seems a hopeless subject. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/116-Wednesday-1st-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 1st May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 spent day working on chemistry went to last choral soc practice in afternoon </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/9-Monday-2nd-May1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 2nd May1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/6-Saturday-3rd-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 3rd May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">bry at 6:00 Smith came down. I spent the day making final preperations for the organic chem. Exam in the evening. Sent letter off to Dorrie which I had written yesterday but had forgotten to post. The exam proved not so bad as I had expected &amp; I think I ought with luck to pass. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/117-Saturday-4th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 4th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">71</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Bry at 9:30 a wet day we had a refreshing shower in the night. I was to have played tennis with the Briggs but the wet put it off. Corly &amp; I went in there instead Mrs Barnes was there we had a nice evening but I found that I had a cold developing. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/118-Sunday-5th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 5th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Had to go to the bry at 1am. Church at 11.0. Went down to brewery after tea found one of the cellar doors undone &amp; on the jar, the one in the upper beer store opening on the yard. Also noticed one of the men, Pettit going into the stables from the lane. Thought that he could get into the yard that way and get through the open door after beer so had decided to bring a book down &amp; spent the evening in the P.A. Bottle store &amp; see if anything happens. I spent nearly an hour there but it struck me that if the door had been opened on purpose by Sprake I would not have been told so I chucked it &amp; went to the &quot;Titanic &quot; concert at the Palace going in about half time. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P33" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/119-Monday-6th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 6th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 6.0 The threatening weather gone Went up to Briggs garden to tennis met Mrs Cambell Caven. Dorothy was also there. Learnt that latter had been sent off to school in the morning but when she got within two mile of Prade she obeyed a sudden impulse to return Her people got a phone message that her luggage had arrived without her &amp; just after she appeared herself as far as I could gather she was severly reprimanded and even in the afternoon her usually cheerful face bore signs of past distress but she brightened up during the evening Had my first game with the new Doherty racket. It was as stiff as a board and emitted a sound s like a banjo, also found it heavy and could not time strokes with any prescision but got better later in the evening Had tea up there &amp; got down to the house about 8.0 I refused to go in &amp; went home to change but Mr Cambell Cavern soon appeased &amp; said I must go down to the house to supper I dressed <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">73</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>hurridly &amp; went down with him He had some music afterwards and although I was very husky they prevailed upon me to sing some indian love lyrics, which I accordingly slaughtered. Mrs Briggs seemed if anything rather weaker than before. Mr Briggs did not get back till late &amp; we did not leave till nearly 12. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/120-Tuesday-7th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 7th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30. Fine day and warm. In the afternoon I went out with Sprake in the trap recently purchased for us we went to Raunds &amp; Stanwicks. Had a very nice afternoon but it was very dull work sitting in the trap with nothing to do.<text:line-break/>We nearly had a nasty accident through colliding with a trolly piled up with empty boxes. Went round to Morrises in the evening. The children are getting over their hoopng cough stopped there to supper.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/121-Thursday-9th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 9th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19">Bry at 10 Another nice day. Went up to the tennis club in the afternoon for the first time I could not play at all <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">4 </text:span>did plenty of work however getting through about 10 sets all of which I lost; at the close of the evening I played some single games with Rowbotham having the advantage by 5 - 3 I was not very much impressed by the play of the others, but perhaps it was because it is the beginning of the season The courts are splendid. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/122-Friday-10th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 10th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0. Rather stiff and left knee was painful. Mrs Sprake came in to tea. Wrote to Popsy Cupper. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/123-Saturday-11th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 11th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0. Met Wallis at Rushden in afternoon &amp; visited Wymington &amp; Rushden churches he came back to tea. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/124-Sunday-12th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 12th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 8 &amp; 11.0 Went to Sprakes to tea &amp; had a walk in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/125-Monday-13th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 13th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Went up to tennis in evening &amp; won two sets. Played with Bearn in one he plays very well. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/126-Tuesday-14th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Tuesday 14th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 10.0 Sir Hubert, Smith &amp; Harman came down. Talked of getting an electric pump for rousing very silly I think. Played tennis in evening but very badly. Went I got back I was very distressed by <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">75</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>a letter from Dorrie. Mother &amp; Father had gone down to Margate for the week-end and on Monday night a man broke in by the breakfast room window. Silenced the dog by giving him a bone he found and turned out all the drawers even went into Dorries room where she was sleeping &amp; took her purse it only had 4s in it though. He did not find the silver luckly. She investigated my room thoroughly and Dorrie wanted to know if there was anything valuable there I could only think of my Bank book &amp; telegraphed that that was there. Wrote later in the evening &amp; afterwards went for a walk with Rowbotham. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/127-Wednesday-15th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 15th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Beautiful mash Wet day first for about two months Went to Morris in evening to supper etc. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/128-Thursday-16th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 16th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19">Bry at 10.0 Showery day &amp; much colder.<text:line-break/>Went to tennis in afternoon gettimg more at home at it. Margorie Briggs turned up. Played very well indeed. Walked down with her afterwards. Got a letter from father telling me that nothing <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">6</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>more had been missed.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/129-Friday-17th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 17th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Went for a sharp ride in evening Grenden &amp; Earls Barton </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/130-Saturday-18th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 18th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Tennis with Briggs in evening could not play at all. Went down to house afterwards with Cavens though we did not want to go because of Mrs Briggs she seemed however rather better. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/131-Sunday-19th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 19th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Went for a ride in afternoon with Rowbotham Grendon Yardley Hastings, Castle Ashby &amp; church in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/134-Monday-20th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 20th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery 6:45 Tennis in evening but could not hit a ball so chucked it. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/132-Tuesday-21st-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 21st May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Got letter from father saying burglars had been arrested, 3 men a woman &amp; a sailor they had done 6 burglaries in a week one of these was proved against them yesterday at 3 Albany Terrace Chatham ours was remanded till next Tuesday, one was at Spencer Woodham&apos;s. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/133-Wednesday-22nd-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 22nd May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Much rain in the night Bry at 6.0 Raining on and off all day. Finest rain for weeks. Went to meeting of Choral Society </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">77</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">in evening at which we decided to ignore the protests of the professional muscisians of the town who are jealous of Terry position as conductor</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P35"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/138-Thursday-23rd-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 23rd May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Very dull day sent parcel off for home. Very cold went up to tennis in evening but found it too wett cold for play. Went for walk round Hardwick &amp; Harrodon instead</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/139-Friday-24th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 24th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Mr Smith came down &amp; decided to have a electric rousing pump also holes made in F.Vs. Wrote an application to the TREANF for a post under the insurance Act. I dont really want anything of the sort but there is no harm in asking and the job seems rather decent £100 - £700 with a pension is&apos;t to be meeged. However I dont expect to hear any more of it not having a labour M.P. At my back. Much better day than yesterday though not too much Wind vearing round from N to E. Went up to tennis a great many there.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/140-Saturday-25th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 25th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">A beautiful morning but rather cold bry 6.15. Started off on a cycle about 10.0 and with a slight northerly wind had a beautiful ride. I took things very easily as far as Bedford but the conditions were so very favourable that I did the journey to Potters Bar in very good time. I took the road to the left at Hitchen &amp; got on to the Great N road at Stevenage. Times &amp; distances as follows<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>10.00 start 50831 3.35 Potters Bar Arr 50399<text:line-break/>12.35 Shefford 5110.9 5.10 Dep<text:line-break/>1.15 Hitchin 18.0 6,40 Channon Str 54.7<text:line-break/>2.3 Knebworth 25.7 7.55 Gravesend 54.8<text:line-break/>2.20 Welwyn 28.8 8.35 Rochester 62.5<text:line-break/><text:line-break/><text:line-break/>Just before I got to Potters Bar I found that my back tyre was leaking but by pumping it up once or twice managed to reach cheesman&apos;s alright this however made my average 10 m.p.h instead of 11.0.<text:line-break/>I got to Canon street just in time to catch the 7.45 for Gravesend the cheap train Did not feel at all distressed although I had done 80 miles in the day.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Notes:<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>George is working in Wellingbourgh his Parents house or home is Rochester he is cyling home by first cycling from Wellingbourgh to Cannon Street London then catching train to Gravesend </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/141-Sunday-26th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 26th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Beautiful day church at 11.0 Cathederal Brows came in in evening.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/142-Monday-27th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 27th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Went up to Violet club to play tennis in evening morning Brous came down in afternoon &amp; we played from 2.30 to 7.30 I played better than I had all the year &amp; <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">79</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>found the old racket still quite useful Brous stopped to supper.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/143-Tuesday-28th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Tuesday 28th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Went up to see William Wooten he has been very ill with swelling in the face &amp; neck but is getting better now.<text:line-break/>Went to the chatham police court in afternoon to hear our case. Dorrie had to give evidence. There were four prisoners <text:line-break/>Sladden, Howell a sailor Hylands &amp; a woman Milton the latter two had been found in possession of some of our stuff. Evidence was given by a man &amp; a women that Sladden had been seen with the cigar &amp; flask we lost but there was no evidence against Howell. The woman was released , Sladdon was committed for trial on our charge the sailor &amp; Howell were also committed but on other charges.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>Went over to Gravesend in evening went for a walk with Huggins who was full of recent expedition to Wicken Fen sailing. Met his sistor again who seems to be a ripping girl also Pa who talked of nothing but snails moths etc to Harry.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/144-Wednesday-29th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 29th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">80</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Up at 6.30 Beautiful morning but hot what slight wind there was in the north. Cycled to gravesend to catch 9:13. To cannon street &amp; rode from there to Bedford. Had tea there &amp; then went to Wallis where I stayed till after seven. Getting back to W just after nine. Went straight up to Sprakes. Times &amp; distances<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>8.10 start 5164.6 1.45 Welwyn 5198.3<text:line-break/>9.0 Gravesend 72.3 3.25 start after lunch 05.3<text:line-break/>10.15 Canon Str 72.4 5.10 Bedford 24.0<text:line-break/>11.57 Potters Bar 87.3 <text:line-break/>12.50 Puncture 89.5 Wellingbourgh 43.8<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>Had another puncture after Potters Bar which delayed me 1/2 hour. Had a wash at a wayside pub about 2.30 where bar kitdhen &amp; scullery was all one &amp; had lunch after. Before lunch I never felt at all happy the day was very oppressive and a left very slack &amp; saddle sore. After I passed Hitchen I pulled myself together a bit and did most of the run to Bedford at 12 m p h. From Bedford to Rushden I also went very well keeping 12 m p h up all the way it then began to get dark</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Notes:<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>I think he gets the train from Gravesend to Cannon Street then cycles from Cannon street to Wellingbourgh</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/135-Thursday-30th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 30th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/>Bry at 6.<text:span text:style-name="T20">15</text:span> where I cleared off a lot of work before breakfast I felt a bit stiff after the ride. Sprake went to a Masonic show at Peterboro&apos;. In the evening I had an hour on the river for the first time. I soon got into it again and seemed to be rowing no worse that last year. The twists in the stream upset me frequently as I was contiually colliding with the bank.<text:line-break/>Rowbotham brought his fiancee in for a minute or two in the evening Miss Francess Hewson of Fetney Lincs. She is staying with his uncle Mr Raines she seems a very nice girl smaller than I had expected and with a very pleasing if not beautiful face </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/136-Friday-31th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Friday 31th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">Wet morning Bry at 6.0. Wilbur Wright the pioneer airman died yesterday he was the first man to fly with any certainty. Rained <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>and off all day with thunder. Went to Palace in evening with Rowbotham Miss Hewson &amp; Miss Hinds. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/137-Saturday-1st-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 1st June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30 very misty morning Briggs to tennis in afternoon Mrs Briggs came up in a cab she was much better. Went down there to supper. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/146-Sunday-2nd-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 2nd June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church @ 11.0 Rainy morning &amp; afternoon slept soundly in afternoon thus partly rid of sleepiness that had been with me all the week. It cleared up in the evening &amp; I went for a walk.<text:line-break/>Wrote to laurtus Mathews to arrange about a visit to Cambridge. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/148-Monday-3rd-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 3rd June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Showery day again. Bry at 6.0 In evening applied for two jobs as under brewer advertising in Brewing Trade Review, said I wanted £160 but would take less for malting, I dont really want to leave yet but would like to get into brewery with malting before October. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/149-Tuesday-4th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 4th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 9:30 very wet day had a tea party in evening entertaining Miss Hewson &amp; Miss Hinds went went very well I think played cards for a little while &amp; then went to the <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">83</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span>Palace saw quite a good show. More taken with Miss Hewson than ever she is I should think quite a man&apos;s girl. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/150-Wednesday-5th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 5th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Cloudy morning &amp; cold Showery during the day. Went round to see Mr Morris in evening Children had had another attack of hooping cough. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/145-Thursday-June-6th-May-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday June 6th May 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Another wet day Bry at 10.0 cleared up in afternoon a bit but had a heavy shower at 2.30. Went up to tennis in evening found match in progress &amp; club loosing played a good single feeling more at home than before october. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/147-Friday-7th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 7th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Fine morning but set in well at 3 o&apos;clock and rained all evening deprived me of a visit to Northampton to see Warwich Match. Mr Smith came down I saw Mrs Smith in the yard &amp; had a conversation with her found her very natural and pleasant. Took Rowbotham &amp; Miss Hewson to the Palace in evening a very good show again. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/151-Saturday-8th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Saturday 8th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">Rained all night Bry at 10.0 Rain stopped at 12 but had made it impossible for Briggs intended tennis party to come off.<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>Went down to bagatelle instead Corby came too Dorothy at home and an old school friend from town, name unknown called by all Evelyn. A very gay girl at first very demure afterwards very much the opposite surprised me by struggling with me for a piece of chalk, this led to much bear play by the others; sat next to her at supper when we carried on a surreptitious game in which she appeared to delight. Altogether she made things very enjoyable. Dorothy also looked very nice Madge with her quiet ways and strangeness to playfulness seemed rather out of it. Mrs Briggs seemed not much better than last Saturday Mrs Barnes still there &amp; very lively.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P36"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/152-Sunday-9th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 9th June 1912</text:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">Church at 8 &amp; 11 where I was joined by Rowbotham Miss Hewson &amp; Miss Hinds took them down to brewery afterwards slept all afternoon, tea with Sprakes Thunderstorm in evening Wrote to Dorrie &amp; Leonard Wallis.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/153-Monday-10th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 10th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30 shower at 6.0 after that a fine morning Letter from Brous.<text:span text:style-name="T20">went up to Briggs for tennis in afternoon had heavy rain &amp; thunderstorm at 4:30 but played on afterwards I heard that Mrs Briggs had been worse &amp; must now be kept quite</text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/154-Tuesday-11th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 11th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">5</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>Bry at 9:45 A beautiful morning It kept fine all day the first fine day since 30th last month. Went up to tennis club in evening only to be more disgusted with my play then ever. Miss Hewson went back this afternoon I saw her when I was in the street this morning and said good bye.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/155-Wednesday-12th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 12th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:00 Another rainy day. Went for a good walk in evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/156-Thursday-13th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 13th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:30 Went up to tennis in evening lost every set as usual met the Miss Parsons for the first time . A fine girl </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/157-Friday-14th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 14th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:00 A beautiful morning went up to tennis in evening had some good games. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/161-Saturday-15th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 15th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1912/1912%20-%200531.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Hendon Airshow</text:a> </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/158-Saturday-16th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/></text:a></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/158-Saturday-16th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 16th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Bry at 10:0 Uncertain day but the rain kept off <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">85 </text:span>Went up to Briggs court for tennis in afternoon. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/159-Sunday-16th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 16th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">Church at 11.0 Blustery morning with <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">6</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>distant thunder. Went to tea with Sprakes &amp; had a good walk with him in evening. Wrote to father. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/160-Monday-17th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 17th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7:0 Dull oppressive day turning wet in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/162-Tuesday-18th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 18th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Fine day an evening Tennis in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/163-Wednesday-19th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 19th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Went for a ride in afternoon with Rowbotham Grendon Yardley Hastings, Castle Ashby &amp; church in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/164-Thursday-20th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 20th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery 6:45 Tennis in evening but could not hit a ball so chucked it. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/165-Friday-21st-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 21st June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Got letter from father saying burglars had been arrested, 3 men a woman &amp; a sailer they had done 6 burglaries in a week one of these was proved against them yesterday at 3 Albany Terrace Chatham ours was remanded till next Tuesday, one was at Spencer Woodham&apos;s. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/166-Saturday-22nd-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"/></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/167-Sunday-23rd-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 23rd June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">87 </text:span>Warm morning Went bathing before breakfast 7:30. Crowds down there water very fine. Church as 11.0 Walk in evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/168-Monday-24th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 24th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:30 Bathing at 7:45 Very few this time. Spent morning investigating my position with regards to Insurance Act. It now appears that as the firm will guarantee to pay my wages for 6 weeks in illness I will have to pay 17s 4d per year. In evening, braving the showers I rode to Thrapston - 11 miles -- Pretty road but hilly. Thrapston quaint town with pretty river. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/169-Tuesday-25th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Tuesday 25th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Very wet morning causing postponment of intended school treat cleared up in afternoon. I got a letter yesterday from Dorrie saying that Mother wished our holiday to be taken in Normandy rather than Belgium as we had arranged. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/170-Wednsday-26th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednsday 26th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry @ 6.20, Fineday but windy Rode in evening to keystone through Raunds. Found Rounds station 11 1/4 miles through Higham Ferrers &amp; 10 3/4 through Irthlingboro </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/171-Thursday-27th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 27th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">Bry at 10.0 Rode out to castle Ashly in <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T38"> </text:span>morning &amp; in evening went for puill on the river. Sunday school treat came off to-day splended weather. Great function. The whole town turned out to see the procession which comprised 4 bands, the vicars supported by their church wardens, church lads brigade etc. Brewery men according to custom had 1 hour off. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/172-Friday-28th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 28th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 5.30. Bathing. Rode out to Castle Ashby in morning. Went to Findon Hall in afternoon with Mrs Balaam. Hall not so imposing as I had anticipated frame good furniture &amp; grounds beautiful . Went to tea with Mrs Wallis, Mrs Balaam&apos;s aunt she keeps a dairy farm On part of what was the Finedon Hall estate. Very genuine family inspected seperating machine. Went to see Mr Morris when I got back he was at home alone Miss having gone to Southhampton.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/173-Saturday-29th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 29th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37">Bry at 9:30 Rain threatened but kept off. Visited Tichmarch where Dryden spent his youth, Peterboro&apos; a<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">9</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">d</text:span>isappointing town but Cathederal splendid shut off from rest of town &amp; &amp;ei;ne 30ths entered by a Norman gateway to which has been added a Perp. facade. Cathederal in form of a single cross.<text:line-break/>Originally Norman &amp; hole of Norm. Nave &amp; choir remain latter terminated by a apse. An early English W.front was added consisting of 3 fine lofty arches in middle one a Pesp porch A splendid Perp chapel was on at E end and walls were pierced through Norman <text:line-break/>The whole church was restored some 30 years ago when central tower was rebuilt. Loquacious verger showed me around &amp; pointed out a graves of Mary Queen of Scots &amp; Catherine of Aragon Town was excited over the visit of the &quot;Daily Mail&quot; airman. Got back without much effort. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/174-Sunday-30th-June-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 30th June 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Times<text:line-break/>Out 1.35 start 78.5<text:line-break/>2.30 Thrapston 88.7<text:line-break/>4.32 Peterboro&apos; 10.6<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>Home 6.30 Pet&apos;bro 12.0<text:line-break/>7.50 Oudle 24.8<text:line-break/>8.33 Thrapstone 32.3<text:line-break/><text:soft-page-break/>9.35 Home 42.6<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>Church at 11.0 Church Parade service Great event for the town. Slept all afternoon. Church at 6:30 &amp; Wallis with Rowbotham after. Found Marjorie Edwards was in to supper More fetching than ever, in fact I am getting rather too keen I think. Resisted temptation to offer to escort her home. Have been wondering more of if I am over cautious. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/175-Monday-1st-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 1st July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6:15 Many complains about dull beers had very busy day. Sprake went to Kettering. Letters from father &amp; Dorrie with good wishes. Yesterday I got some handkerchiefs &amp; a belt from home, the latter too large for me. Went up to tennis in evening but found things very slack. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/176-Tuesday-2nd-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 2nd July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:45: Mr Sprake went to Moulton more trouble with beers Mr Sprake came in in morning. Rained or rather dryzled continuously all day. Palace in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/177-Wednesday-3rd-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 3rd July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 7.0 Another dull day still trouble Went to Kettering to fine down some beers got very dirty. Rain spoilt tennis in evening went to Exchange to see film of Church parade blurred </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/178-Thursday-4th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 4th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">91</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>Bry at 10.0 Mr Sprake gone to Rushden more trouble. Rode to Sywell &amp; fined down two brls of P.A Trip took only 1 hour .<text:line-break/>Tennis in afternoon &amp; evening. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/179-Friday-5th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 5th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 5.40 Better day Tennis in evening met with more success than usual Sir H &amp; Mr Smith came down. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/180-Saturday-6th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 6th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">6th Bry at 6:30 Prepared for ride to Nott fine morning with fresh E wind . Started at 9:15 caught as I was leaving the town by girls selling paper wild roses for the hospitals there is a fete being held today for them. Took an hour to get to kettering road after that hilly to Desborough, running along the tops of hills with frquent steep dips after Desborough more level with steep hill into Market Harbourgh. Good cycling road from there to Leicestershire M.H a nice country town with a very wide street. Leister a fine prosperous looking town Road from 2 1/2 miles out lined with large houses in spacious grounds Up to date trams etc; fine market place &amp; municipal buildings Had a cheap lunch and left for Loughboro at 1:45 Road to Loughborough good fell in with a companion. Parsed through &amp; Mount Sorrel. Former home of famois pack ; latter seat of large granite quarries. Loughborough a very low class town. Missed the turn to Nottm &amp; went a mile beyond had to come back. Road to Nott more hilly &amp; wind made itself felt. Got into Nott at 4.45. Followed trams through Bullwell to Bestwood. A very bad route They say the Best way to cycle is via the Mansfield <text:soft-page-break/>road. Reached Bestwood at 5.30 nearly an hour later than I intended Found Uncle &amp; Aunt at home &amp; well Girls <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I16950&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged&amp;tab=0" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Dorothy</text:a> and <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I16945&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged&amp;tab=0" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Nellie </text:a>came in after 9.0 D. much improved through greater contact with the world and even shows signs of becoming a coquette with the help of a rather fine pair of eyes. Nellie also appears less ????? (napour ?) has given up her vegetarianism since her engagement. Sat up till 12. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Note <text:line-break/><text:line-break/>George is cycling from Wellingbourgh to see his <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I13459&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Aunt Jane</text:a> <text:span text:style-name="T38">Parsons </text:span>and <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I16943&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.gedhttp://" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">George Fredrick Downar</text:a> who live at <text:line-break/>18 Bestwood Colliery<text:line-break/>Bestwood Park<text:line-break/>Nottinghamshire<text:line-break/><text:line-break/>Bestwood Colliery Nr Nottingham <text:line-break/>Nellie (Helen) Married Phillip Wale 29th Sep<text:line-break/>18 Rothesay Av Nottingham <text:line-break/>Phillip was a lacedesigner </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/181-Sunday-7th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 7th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38">Up at 9.15. Walk in morning with Dorothy Nellie met up. Sleep in after walk Mr Wale, Nellies fiance&apos;e appeared <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">93</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>for tea He is obviously a crank. Very nervous man with a pair of spectacled beady eyes and a brown beard with signs of grey age about 40 A man whose character </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/182-Monday-8th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 8th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Up at 7.15 breakfast at 8.0 left by train <text:span text:style-name="T38">Nellie and Dorothy </text:span>sent bag on by train as morning was threatening and wind S_W_ every promise of a unpleasant ride . This was quite fulfilled Took the route back via Melton Mobury hilly and wind was a great nuisance. Showers also occasionally. Melton Mow. a good old fashioned own of fair size Ride to oakam increasingly unpleasant; and as a my left knee gave me some anxiety I began to think about train. Never very strong I apparently over strained this on Sat. It was ina very doubtfulstate on Sunday morn but afterwards recovered. However the work brought back a pain<text:line-break/>Found I could get a trian at Kettering at 1.04 so decided to do so.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/183-Wednesday-10th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 10th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Rode to Dsbourgh in morning trained back from K. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/185-Saturday-13th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 13th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37">Bry at 6.00 Early breakfast &amp; started on bicycle with Dorrie at 7.40 to catch 8.45 train at Raunds. Had to ride hard to do it (10.7 miles) but caught train successfully putting likes up at one of our pub near the station consists of one long platform and is about a mile from the centre of the town. <text:soft-page-break/>Walked up to town looked in R.C church Very fine modern gothic. Emmanuel college Christs College. St Mary Church the great (Very fine church spoilt by galleries erected later corpus Christi college. Pembrook &amp; its chapel by Wren &amp; fine Combination room. Penthouse,the oldest college in the varsity with its curous chapel half gothic half renaissance and beautiful Combination room with Burne Jones windows. Then we had lunch afterwards saw St Benedict church saxon tower. Then went on to Kings found Luartus Mathews had expected us to lunch. Visited the fine college chapel. A truly wonderful building lofty &amp; very rich, beautiful wooden organ screen He also took us round Trinity &amp; Queens <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">97</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>the later very pictureque with it&apos;s timbered buildings. Trinity rather sombre, partly built by wren. We then went on the river, the prettiest bit of water I have ever seen I think. I had my first shot at punting were caught in a thunderstorm ( it was a very hot day) and took refuge under a bridge, were some other undergrads also up for the long entertained us with a gramaphone. Back to Luartus rooms to a very fine tea He has a beautiful rooms. Caught train back with a rush. Visited Raundschurch very fine withremains of some beautiful old fredcoes good E.F tower, on to Hignam Ferrers where we chatted with the vicar. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/186-Sunday-14th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 14th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church with Dorrie at 8.0 &amp; 11.0 Rested in afternoon Tea with Sprakes &amp; walk</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/198-15th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">15th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.30. Bathing. In evening Dorrie went for drive with Mrs Balaam. Miss Hunphrey in Mr Balaams house I followed on byclelette went Wollerton Bageat Eastern Maudit. Dec church floor tiled with vey fine tiles. Good Ely bethan tomb, Banness etc of local anuent family back G Grendon Very pleasant evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/187-Wednesday-17th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 17th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Another beautiful dy; bathing at 6.0 Busy dy on Brewery alone Sprake moving house Went down to All Saints tennis club in evening. found courts very busy. Also made a poor show Miss Hynes came in to supper we played cards afterwards but a concert was going on next door at the Weslian Chapel which demoralised us. So we went out into the garden and applauded their efforts with a four part sneeze </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/188-Thursday-18th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 18th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">99</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>Bry at 6.0 Dull morning walk with Dorrie in evening and Palace with Roubotham &amp; Miss Hynes </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/189-Friday-19th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 19th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.30 Cold morning bathing. Rain Went over to Finedon in afternoon Dorrie with Mrs Balaam &amp; Freda in Mrs Balaam&apos;s trap; I rode Caught in rain and had to change into Bert Wallis socks &amp; shoes. Had a look round their farm. got back about 9.0 to find mother had written saying Dor. must go back on Monday we had arranged for her to stop till Thurs. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/190-Saturday-20th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 20th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Outing Up at 3.15 Breakfast at 4.0 Very misty morning Train left NW stat at 5.0 Had compartment in 3rd corridor cars to ourselves Stopped for water at <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_railway_station" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Brandon</text:a> when Dorrie &amp; I joined the men in their saloon &amp; travelled in that to Yarmouth Passed Ely &amp; Norwich Went down to front at Yarmouth with Mr Waldon &amp; Sprakes then back to quay &amp; took boat to Lowestoft; they all went to sleep on the boat. Rained towards close of trip so we went ashore &amp; listened to the land on the pier drizled all the time Very miserable. Had lunch at the Imperial opposite the station, they did us very well. Meanwhile it cleared up nicely &amp; the sun came out. We went and sat on the beach and all went to sleep again. Roused ourselves at 3 &amp; Dorrie &amp; I had a bathe. First time had been in the sea for 3 years had a splendid bathe, watched a Punch &amp; Judy show for a few minutes then caught boat back at 4.0 Splendid trip back. Had good tea then left Walden &amp; Sprake &amp; made for St Nicolas Church Very interesting indeed. Very large &amp; furniched good examples of all the styles &amp; transistions. Train back at 8.0 Reached W at 12.45 to find we had to walk home in a dryzle Dulleys who went in the same train with us had a misfortune to lose one of their men. A very strong swimm</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/201-Sunday-21th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 21th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Breakfast at 11.0 Walk Sleep in afternoon Morrises after tea. Fine day </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/191-Monday-22nd-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 22nd July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">101</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>By at 6.30. Dull morning. Bathed Much rain later, Dorrie went to tea with Briggs. Played Bagatelle. Met Mr Briggs cousin also named Briggs stained glass manufacturer very amusing man. Mirs Briggs seems much better. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/192-Tuesday-23rd-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 23rd April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">In spite of threatening morning Dorrie &amp; I set out for Geddington Cross very fine but not so good asa Northhampton one. Church newly restored interesting visited Weekley on way back also Kettering &amp; Isham. Got some rain before we got home. Bad thunderstorm in afternoon. Went to Hinds in eveing had a amusing time at cards </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/193-Wednesday-24th-April-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 24th April 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.30 Bathe. Went for walk with Dorrie in evening.Palace better show than before Finer day </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/194-Thursday-25th-July-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 25th July 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30. Mrs Sprake left for her holiday. Dorrie went home by 1.25 train. Tennis in afternoon.Very slack afternoon could not play a bit. Fine warm day. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/195-Friday-26th-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Friday 26th 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 5.30 Bathe. Fine morning Rain at mid-day Tennis in eveing Play singles with Cherry lost &amp; won 6 - 8 , 7 - 5. PLayed very badly indeeed. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/199-Saturday-27th-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 27th 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bathing in morning.Bry at 9.30 Much rain in morning making tennis impossible. The rain was so heavy that the drains overflowed in several places. Walk with Sprake in afternoon. He came in to tea </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/200-Sunday-28th-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 28th 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0. Brewery afterwards, took some photos. Sprake to Dinner More rain in afternoon. Walk after tea Sprake back to supper. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/202-Monday-29th-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 29th 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.30. Bathing spent the whole day working on new book giving trade of pubs developing photos in evening. Rain </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/204-Tuesday-30th-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 30th 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37">Received letter from Lamb Brewer Frome in answer to my application for job advertised in Journal. Wrote them asking for £160 I am not keen on going as brewey seems too small although it has maltings and going there now will mean the sacrifice of the holiday trip to Normandy we have arranged for, in fact I won&apos;t get nay holiday at all. Rained all morning <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">103</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> </text:span>but cleared up in the evening sufficient enough for tennis. Worked late on new trade ledger </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/203-Wednesday-31st-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 31st 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 5.30. Rained all day. Found when I went for my money that I had to pay Mr Briggs 1/- for Insurance. Worked a late again on ledger. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/196-Thursday-1st-August.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 1st August</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Better day than for sometime past, quite a change as it has rained almost incessantly for more than a fortnight, in fact it has become quite rare to see the sun. Worked hard on stocks in morning Tennis in after- with Briggs. Miss Evelyn -- was there a saucy wench, played with more confidence and certainty than ever have before this year. ground was slow which helped me. Went down to house afterwards Mrs Briggs still improving Rowbotham left for C L B Camp at Lytham </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/206-Monday-5th-August.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Monday 5th August</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I was very satisfied with the result I left Sprake with Corly to go home by train but found out afterwards that they had to walk &amp; Sprake had an awefull job to drag Corly along as he wanted to run off with ervery bit of skirt he saw. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/205-Tuesday-6th-August.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 6th August</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 another blowy and wet miserable morning. Rained on and off all day evening Palace with Sprake </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/207-Thursday-8th-August.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 8th August</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 better morning but rained later. Went down in afternoon to Tournument and saw some finals played off in the rain Ingram who had been playing in the torunament at Rochester as he has frequently before steady racing game letting the racket and lost the second set 6 -3 after forcing the first to 13 -11. <text:line-break/>B.W.V Baumgastner who comes from Bedford got into 4 finals </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/208-Friday-9th-August.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 9th August</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">bry 5.30. finer day. Rowbotham came back from cap. Sprake left for Wotton under edge. went for ride to brixworth in evening but could not get into old church countyout that way very fine. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/209-Monday-12th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 12th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.30. Very cold morning in fact weather has degenerated into november without fires is awfull they say the gulf stream has goen wrong and the heat has passsed onto russia rode in evening to Podington and back by Rushden. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/210-Thursday-15th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 15th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Went for a ride in the aftern with Mr Morris got as far as Hardwich when it came onto rain I got a puncture Sywell &amp; Mears Ashby </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/212-Friday-16th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 16th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Beautifull morning but broke up later Smith came down I showed him around Went to Hines in evening &amp; played Bridge </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/213-Saturday-17th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 17th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">109 </text:span>Saturday By at 7.0 Wretched day again Impossbile to go out. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/214-Sunday-18th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Sunday 18th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 and in evening quite a nice day for once with one shower about 2.0. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/211-Monday-19th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 19th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.30 Stormy day with a very bad thunderstorm about two. Heavy showers at times got a letter from Dorrie which gave me a rather shock Allen has been staying at home he has got a job in Egypt which he has been after as a travelling inspector of schools &amp; technical colleges. Dorrie writes &amp; Dad doesnt think we ought to be formaly engaged. I can not think why, because he seems to agree to out getting married next year. They are getting on it seems; she also says she is going to his home at Burnley after our holidays. I don’t like the look of things at all. The fellow a very decent sort certainly but the only thing remarkable about him is that he is a genius and I don&apos;t think that that is a perfect guarantee of happiness. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/215-Tuesday-20th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 20th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Letter from father saying that if bad weather continues Normandy<text:line-break/>trip must be cancelled But we are all meet at Waterloo at 3.0 on Saturday and go somewhere A very casual arrangement Certainly. Another bad day. Sprake got back in afternoon </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/216-Wednesday-21th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 21th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Beautiful morning road over two Rothwell shower or two but fine again after until evening when it rained hard </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/217-Thursday-22th-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 22th August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 splendid day best dy for weeks. Went to the Rushden in mourning and Earls Barton in afternoon. No rain at all. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/218-Friday-23rd-August-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 23rd August 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 5.30. dismal morning with scotch mist. Rained all day poor prospect for holiday tomorrow. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/225-Sunday-8th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 8th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">111 </text:span>I now find myself at the 18th September with no entry signs the 23rd of last month. In another book I recorded my doing during my holiday in France and my expenses would Dorrie on a cycle tour from Dinard to Caen. That account ends with an night of Sunday, Sept 8 so I must no go back and see what I remember since then </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/226-Monday-9th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 9th September 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Was a nice fine day I did very little. Mr &amp; Mrs Bowden who had been looking after the house while we were away went home I went for <text:s/>a walk with father in the evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/227-Tuesday-10th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 10th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I left by the 8.23 train going up with Brous Sayers and Gower. Changed to cycling things at Waterloo and got my bicycle. I stopped at Gamages to buy a ruck-sach and then on through Barnet to St Albans. I had a look at the most interesting cathedral there and had the luck to fall in with a young clergyman who took me round. Leaving the town I was misdirected &amp; got on the to the Dunstable road instead of a Luton one. I had to strike across country and was overtaken by a shower I stood up for some time but had to go on the bench to as the rain showed every prospect of increasing and I got to live and station very wet I had made up my mind to train from here as there was a step which they can win and going was very difficult I got to wellingborough station after 5 &amp; found all well went &amp; saw Sprake in evening he told me one of our men had crushed his fingers in the sugar hoist soon after I left. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/228-Wednesday-11th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 11th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 I found that I was to be presented with a prize (5/-) for my class in organic chemistry. I chose a book on the Hop Plant. Developed photos in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/229-Thursday-12th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 12th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.15 Busy getting books up to date More developing in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/230-Friday-13th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 13th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Went out to Earls Barton and Sywell after dinner. In evening went to see the Lady of Ostend very amusing. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/231-Saturday-14th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 14th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37">Found in morning that Mrs Balaam was unwell and was stopping in bed. The charwoman got us our breakfast <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">113</text:span> and carried on generally but we had to have our dinner at the cosy cafe&apos;. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/232-Sunday-15th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 15th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">For it appeared that Mrs Balaam had been very bad, previous dy. The woman still carried on and got dinner for us. Went to church at 8.0, 11.0 &amp; 6.30 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/233-Monday-16th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 16th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0. Beautiful morning I went out to Desborough. Came back from there (13 miles) in 65 minutes. Evelyn Wallis came in from Finedon and to got us our dinner. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/234-Tuesday-17th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 17th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Got down to find a letter from Carl Wooton by express Post. Tells me or that there is likely to be a vacancy at Hancocks at £120 and would I like to put in for it if so wire him yes. I did. Wrote him asking if he was leaving or the &amp; also whether I could learn malting there. Also applied for job advertised &quot;Daily Telegraph&apos;. Wrote father about Hancocks. Spent evning writing notes on brewery </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/235-Wednesday-18th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 18th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0. Higgins&apos; men started and masonary work for the new copper. Took photos of the brewery yard. Wrote to Dorrie who is still at Burnley Mrs Balaam came down stairs </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">11</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">4 </text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/237-Thursday-23th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 23th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">By at 6.0 Sprake away. Doctor called on Mrs Balaam just she had been making beds found her heart in a bad state. She must do no work at all for six weeks<text:line-break/>The woman she has got in seems to be shaping alright so she will have to take on.<text:line-break/>Ordered a new spring overcoat. Went to palace in evening. Good show. Applied to Hancocks for job. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/236-Friday-24th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 24th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 5-30. Executed great changes in the arrangment of the brewing room. Dorrie came in about 12 &amp; I went out with her. She caught the 3.8 train for St Albans &amp; was to go on from there after having a look around. Went over to Rushden to Station Hotel. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/220-Sunday-25th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 25th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Wednesday By at 6.0 Went over to Rushden again in morning. Went to Morrises in eveing found them all well first time for a year. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/221-Monday-26th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 26th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">when I could leave &amp; what let expenses I had had answered in evening. In afternoon rode out with Rowbotham to Geddington took photo of cross. Developed them in evening. Rowbotham joined me in Brewry. Replied to Aunt Jennies invitation accepting. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/238-Tuesday-27th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 27th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 5-30 Beautiful morning. Took photos of some of office staff developed them in evening also went to Palace. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/223-Wednesday-28th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 28th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9:30 Letter from Hancock asking for interview on Monday or Tuesday wired would come tuesday Would they pay expences got a wire to say defer visit writing. Went to Northhampton cross Photography Heard joke . Two boys took up position behind me when I was packing up one pushfull other timid. Pushfull one He&apos;ll take yer clock if yer want &apos;im to. 2nd on: Wat, ter be mended!!! Received dig in the ribs &amp; explanations. Evening turned dull &amp; dreary </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/224-Thursday-29th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 29th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Mr Briggs bought Mrs B &amp; she fainted Went to Dinner with Sprakes, walk in afternoon &amp; tea. Developed in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/239-Friday-30th-September-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 30th September 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">11</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> </text:span>Dullish dy. Spent most of time printing photographs. Wore light overcoat for first time </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/240-Saturday-1st-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Saturday 1st October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">now been here a year. <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">11</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">7</text:span>Dullish dy made up yearly accounts. Found I spent £95 . 14 . 101/2. increase of some £4 . 10 . 0. Increase has been in special expenses in accounting for by £4. 8 . 9 spent on Tennis and £4.4.8 1/2 on holiday </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/336-Monday-3rd-Oct-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 3rd Oct 1912</text:a></text:h>
