       </office:binary-data>
      </draw:image>
     </draw:frame></draw:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">1912 3 Oct Wellingbourgh Campbell Praed &amp; co Mr Sprake head brewer</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 9.30 Took more photos of office staff and some others. Went for ride with Rowbotham to Bedford. Came back through Turvey &amp; Bogeat made it 19.4 miles this was. much more pretty but rather more hilly. completely ride in dark Develop photos</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/337-Friday-4th-Oct-1913.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 4th Oct 191</text:a><text:span text:style-name="T20">2</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 5:30 beautiful day cold morning went to sywell in afternoon whist drive in </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P40" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T20">Monday</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/337-Friday-4th-Oct-1913.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"> <text:span text:style-name="T20">6</text:span>th Oct 191</text:a><text:span text:style-name="T20">2</text:span></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="P41" text:outline-level="4">Even to the extent of </text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="P40" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T20">Monday</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/337-Friday-4th-Oct-1913.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"> <text:span text:style-name="T20">7</text:span>th Oct 191</text:a><text:span text:style-name="T20">2</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P42"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T29">21</text:span>The Balkan ountries Bularia, Servia Montenegro, Greece beleve that turkey is s weakened by the wa with Italy abd by internal </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/241-Saturday-8th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 8th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 6 felt sore throat for the cold morning clearing up later letter from home palace in the evening poorish show</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/248-Wednsday-9th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednsday 9th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 6.30 throat still bad Foggy again. Rode to Northampton sywell in afternoon beautiful afternoon and country look splendid.<text:line-break/>This morning papers told us that in spite of a long negotiations Montenegro had declared war on Turkey so the match has been struck it remains to be seen what size firewall result. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/249-Thursday-10th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 10th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 9.30 Reported Montenegrian veto went for a ride with Rowbotham in afternoon for Brixworth &amp; Sywell. Beautiful afternoon. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/250-Friday-11th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 11th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 6.0. Letter from Wallis saying he cant come this week, I had asked him over the week end. I asked him if he could come on 26th. </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/251-Saturday-12th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 12th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">Brewery at 10 letter from father saying W or what was worse and the doctors give him a only three weeks from glass at road in afternoon no which through the park and Drayton hall historically very interesting church remarkable for old stained glass and lantern of <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">23</text:span>tower passed on to break stopped but could not get into church. Intended to make for geddington but got into Stanion. Left there are 3 min to five got back home at 6.3 Kettering 5.38 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/252-Sunday-13th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 13th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 8.0 with the Rowbotham. parish at 11.0. Walk with R round 3 mile spin in afternoon Church in evening &amp; short walk Wrote to father. telling him I would be up in town on Wed 23rd By train leaving here at 8.0</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/247-Monday-14th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 14th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 6.30 from this morning papers we see that Turkey is in reply to use Serbians demand that she should do more demobilise for troops has thrown 3,000 men across thus serve be an frontier in evening attended a lecture on our parish church in the middle ages collection told us that most church choose were the region A uniform with the outer isles and aisles were added afterwards so destroying the cruciform plan also authority was the custom for the rector&apos;s to keep in repair the chancel while the parish and is repaired the nave hence partly the importance of the rood screen showed some splendid views </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/246-Tuesday-15th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 15th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">24 </text:span>Br<text:span text:style-name="T20">y</text:span> at 6.15 Turkey concluded a piece with Italy yesterday and is now free to tackle the Balkans in the journal which arrived today there were no vacancies advertised us plenty of brewers wanting jobs. Spent evening reading the &quot;Times printing supplement.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/245-Wednesday-16th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 16th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 10 I have been suffering since Sunday with a painful cuts in the mouth but is rather better this morning </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/244-Thursday-17th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 17th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry attend splendid ayr road to market harborough in afternoon with Rowbotom had seen the town then called on some friends of his started back at 65 home by 7.55 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T42">F</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/243-Friday-18st-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">riday 18st October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at six per acre went to Northampton two installation of provincial grandmaster in afternoon palace in the evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/242-Saturday-19th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 19th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">Heard from home at William Wotton died on Thursday at 1.30 PM it is very sad he was so promising a chemist that he would probably have earned made a distinction had he lived and he was such a splendid son. <text:span text:style-name="T20">H</text:span>e had fulfilled in a wonderful <text:span text:style-name="T2">thorough manner the respons </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">5 </text:span>for remember the first bet</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P43" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/242-Saturday-19th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">S<text:span text:style-name="T2">un</text:span>day <text:span text:style-name="T2">20</text:span>th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/253-Monday-21th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 21th October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.30. Dull dy Sprake spent morning with dentist </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/254-Tuesday-22nd-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 22nd October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 10.0 Tody is the dy of William Woottons funeral. Went to Dowling Club Whist Drive in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/255-Wednesaday-23rd-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Wednesaday 23rd October 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">caught 8.0 Train to town Very foggy 40 min. late at St.P. Met Father &amp; Mother at charring X. and went with them to SK where we met Dorrie. Had lunch together at corner house Then I made for the show . got there at 2.0. The beers we put in got not . Disappointed in meeting Duhinson I saw no one else <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">7 </text:span>see Dickinson it turned out there was a dinner being given by Rosenf<text:span text:style-name="T2">e</text:span>lds Mr. and Mrs. seveyed ? me &amp; dragged me into it. I sat next Duly very good dinner left to catch my train at 8-15 Home at 10.45. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/256-Thursday-24th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 24th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Sprake has gone up to show today Briggs has invited me to dinner therefore summer after next road thanks to me for his hospitality I must apologise for Lisa last night at such an early her bus or train which like the trade winds waits for no man compelled it.<text:line-break/>Did I thank you hardly for only for an exceedingly good enjoyable dinner but also for your your tremendous hospitality he took stranger like myself to share it.&quot; </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/257-Friday-25th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 25th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By @ 6.30 brewing strong Ale which kept me busy all dy.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/258-Saturday-26th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 26th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 9.30. Had lunch with Mrs Ballam at 1.15 &amp; went to meet Wallis afterwards Wretched wet dy. Spent afternoon in brewery. Went to Palace in evening Rowbotham join us later. Good show. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/259-Sunday-27th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 27th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37">Breakfast at 10.0 Wallis went on All Saints with Rowbothom I went to <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">128 </text:span>the parish church had walk with Wallace in afternoon church at All Saints in evening. Rotten day </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/260-Monday-28th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 28th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Brewery at 6.0 Wallis left by the 8.12 train. It appears from the papers that all hope is at an end for the Turks but one cannot help thinking that they must have something up their sleeve. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/262-Tuesday-29th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 29th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/261-Wednesday-30th-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 30th October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 Raining hard. Harman &amp; Smith came down &amp; we had lunch with them in the house. I spoke to Harman about a change &amp; although he did not want to make the firm unsettled he promised to remember it. choral Soc practicing in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/263-Thursday-31st-October-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 31st October 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I have five at 10.0. Fromwash of the new copper completed. Went for walk with Rowbotham in afternoon church institute in evening. Played my first game of billiards and skittles. At former scored 50 in are our including one stroke a six day arrested at skittles </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/264-Friday-1st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 1st November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0. very cold morning Mrs. Sprake came to T in evening went to institute played skittles and billiards again</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/265-Saturday-2nd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>Saturday 2nd November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0 Morning papers tell us that the Turkish Macedonian army has been routed so that Constantinople alone remains. Went for ride to Ringstead and the Addingtons river in flood necessitaty carrying bicycle along a plank causeway in one place church of Gr Addington very interesting too dark to see Lit Addington. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/266-Sunday-3rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 3rd November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 briggs at a lunch Mr. and Mrs. Barnes there took some photos in afternoon wash with corly and young Hurt there to T and every left at 11.0 went into Perkins who had come over left their at 11.45</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/267-Monday-4th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 4th November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">by at six finished telling their new <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">30</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18"> </text:span>&quot;Copper&quot; this ought to have been done before any .was put in it at all. Wreched damp dg Developed photos in evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T2">Tuesday </text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/269-5th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">5th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0. Had row with Brewry man Page in evening he swore at me when I grumbled at his clumsiness &amp; in the course of subseqent proccedings he showed himself to be drunk. he must go. Spent evening reading. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/270-6th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">6th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.15. Page was given a weeks notice he pleaded for leniency on the grounds that he must be married shortly but I persuaded Sprake to be firm. Palace in Evening. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/272-Thursday-7th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 7th November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 9.30, Washed late in brewey. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/273-Friday-8th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 8th November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Bry at 6.0 Smith &amp; Sir Herbert came down spend most of morning selecting hops with Sprake. Got away by 3. train same as Sir Herbert: Met Dorrie at SK. Went to &quot;A Scrape o&apos; the Pen&quot; enjoyed it immensly. Corner House afterwards Dorry 11.40. Rochester 1.0. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/274-Saturday-9th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Saturday 9th November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Spent most of the morning taking photos of Father Mother Dorrie <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I701&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged&amp;tab=2" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Aunt Emily</text:a> developed them in evening. They came out well. Brous came in he sits for his Inter exam in 18th. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/275-Sunday-10th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Sunday 10th November 1912 </text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 8 also at 10.30. Mayors Sunday. Went up to Wooton&apos;s in evening saw Carl &amp; went for walk with him He told me about Watneys &amp; their 16,000 - 20,000 bls per week. I dont think he can get much valuable experiance there though. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/276-Monday-11th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Monday 11th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Up to town by 7.45. Went down to Fulham &amp; spent morning there. Saw Dorrie afterwards I told her she ought not to think of getting married next June but wait another year &amp; get a job in the <text:soft-page-break/>meanwhile Walked in kensington gardens. Called in at Charrn X Rd on the my walk to St Pancras Wellingboro at 4.18. NSL meeting in evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/277-Tuesday-12th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Tuesday 12th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">By at 6.0 Rowbotham staggered me at breakfast by saying that Miss Hewson has brocken off their engagment. He was terribly cut up about it and I hope they will make it up. They alwats seemed so fond of each other. The Gov. were defeated in the House yesterday on an <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">32</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18"> </text:span>amendment moved of Sir F Barbury restricting the money grant to Ireland under the Home Rule Bill to £2,500,000 a year. It is announced however that they are going to take another division on the subject:contrary to all precedent. In any case they cannot resign just now in consequence of the uncertain position of things on the C<text:span text:style-name="T2">o</text:span>ntinent. The Turks have driven right back onto constantinople &amp; Salonica has fallen. Austria is now getting ancious as to what the victorous States use going to do. Spent evening printing photos. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/278-Wednesday-13th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Wednesday 13th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 Went over to Rushden &amp; had to ride back through a cold rain. Choral soc in evening. Rowbotham hinted that I might write to Miss Hewson I had already decided to if they did not make it up so I assented he obviously did not know what to do. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/279-Thursday-14th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Thursday 14th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P39">By at 10.0 I wrote a long letter to Miss Hewson pointing out that Rowbothams&apos; failure to go down to Tetney the nominal cause of the break was quite <text:span text:style-name="T10">1/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">1</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">33</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18"> </text:span>unavoidable. At tea he showed me the letter from his father which had apparently decided him to write her that he accepted the position, as he had done tha afternoon; still I had written my letter &amp; I thought that as any rate it could do no harm and I was sure that reconciliation would be welcome to him. He is very cut up about it. Spent evening at the Institute when I got back I found a brace of pheasants awaiting me they had been sent by Mrs Briggs I was very annoyed. Apparently they dont want to take some photos of mine I had promised them without making some return se behold! a brace of pheasants </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/280-Friday-15th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Friday 15th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0. I was all wrong about those birds they are from Sir Herbert but were forwarded by on of Mrs Briggs work girls. I cant make up my mind as to Rowbothams feelings towards Miss Hewson and references at dinner to Miss Smith &amp; her fathers nice little tobacconist business did not tend to ease things, still perhaps it was quite accidental evening at Institute </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P44"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P45" text:outline-level="4">Starting a new Diary Book </text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="P46" text:outline-level="4">November 1912</text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/197-16th-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">16th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">My notes in this new book must necessarily start with the affairs of another than of myself. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T43">Got a letter from Miss Hewson from which I gather that she had repented of her folly R. showed me one from her mother which taken in conjunction with mine the other showed that if R went down there this week and everthing would be alright again. I told him that &amp; left him struggling betweeb his pride &amp; his affections.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T43">If he goes he must be away from C.L.B. wedding I am still doubtfull as to his feelings and am worring left my interference may have helped to bring about a union that us undesirable Rowbotham however has not gone I must therefore conclude that his affections has. Went to the Northhampton in afternoon left 2.55 got in again 4.55 good afternoon for cycling. Print</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44">ery in evening.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T45">17th</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/281-21st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T46"> November 1912</text:span></text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Church at 11.0 Had pheasants given &amp; Sir H Praed for dinner walk with Sprake in afternoon these to tea more printing in evening. Back to rooms to supper in fromt room with Mrs B Miss Humphrys walked home with her afterwards; she was charming got up to her house latter part very slowly then suggested a little longer walk, she agreed bt she had to get in at last: It is worth of note that this Is the first time I have voluntary undertaken a&amp; this and a vg good subject too g consider for such an attempt.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P47" text:outline-level="4"><office:annotation office:name="__Annotation__4321_3425459006" loext:resolved="false">
     <dc:creator>Unknown Author</dc:creator>
     <dc:date>2025-05-24T19:50:06.917288800</dc:date>
     <text:p text:style-name="Comment">From page 3 of second diary</text:p>
    </office:annotation><text:span text:style-name="T45">18th</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/281-21st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T47"> November 1912</text:span></text:a><office:annotation-end office:name="__Annotation__4321_3425459006"/></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 6.30 spent evening on photos after supper discussed with Mrs B &amp; Miss H at th giving of a private shist drive.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">*^&amp;*</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P47" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T45">19th</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/281-21st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T46"> November 1912</text:span></text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">*&amp;*&amp;^*&amp;</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Played billiards at the church Institude in evening with more confidence but little success.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P47" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T45">20th</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/281-21st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T46"> November 1912</text:span></text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 6.30 Had curous demonstrating of the value of bounce. <text:span text:style-name="T44">When I was in London <text:s/>on Monday week I called at Foyles the 2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T48">nd</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44"> hand booksellers &amp; bought two booka &amp; left a deposit for a Hooper.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T44">This they sent but I was not satisfied with it so sent it back &amp; asked them to send the Brewers Analyst “G Bailey” which I had seen these marked 5/6 at the same time I pointed out that they</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44"><office:annotation loext:resolved="false">
      <dc:creator>Unknown Author</dc:creator>
      <dc:date>2025-05-24T19:51:26.157787000</dc:date>
      <text:p text:style-name="Comment">From page 4 second diary</text:p>
     </office:annotation></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44"> had charged 4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T48">d </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44">for the postage which was only 3</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T48">d. </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T49">They sent the Brewers Analyst but in the account charged 7/6 (they had &amp; the was corrected the postage error making the balance 5/6. I sent them ¾ $ said they would get the reset. When the charge in price was explaioned smith came down</text:span></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/281-21st-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:soft-page-break/>21st November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 10.0. Most wretched dg In evening went to Park Street Schools Social &amp; dance with Rowbotham &amp; Miss Hymes had a very good time with Miss Scott Rowbotham&apos;s assistant. Miss Gent was very prominent. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T23">2</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://old.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/282-22nd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">2nd November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 9.30. Much better dy.In evening went to Palace &amp; saw a rather lurid Melodrama White as a Lily? </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">23rd November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 5-45 bouled up spent hops </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48"><office:annotation office:name="__Annotation__4557_3425459006" loext:resolved="false">
     <dc:creator>Unknown Author</dc:creator>
     <dc:date>2025-05-24T19:54:22.265250600</dc:date>
     <text:p text:style-name="Comment">Second diary page 5</text:p>
    </office:annotation>in new copper. Went<office:annotation-end office:name="__Annotation__4557_3425459006"/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"/></text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">2<text:span text:style-name="T44">4th</text:span> November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">Church at 11.00 Mr Smeaton preached a stiring sermon on the growth of Canada <text:s/>&amp; </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P50"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">2<text:span text:style-name="T44">5th</text:span> November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">Bry at 6.30 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P50"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">2<text:span text:style-name="T44">6th</text:span> November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">By at 9:30 Horrible day</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4">2<text:span text:style-name="T44">7</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">By at 6.0</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4">2<text:span text:style-name="T44">8</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">By at 9.30 </text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T44">29</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">By at 6.0</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T44">30</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">th November 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P48">Turning much colder</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P49" text:outline-level="4"><text:span text:style-name="T48"><text:s/></text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/index.php?/archives/283-23rd-November-1912.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T44">9 December</text:span> 1912</text:a></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P50"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Tuesday 14th January 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Father&apos;s birthday, I believe he is 62. Bry at 10.0. Thawing rapidly Mrs Spake came to tea Wellingbourgh </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Monday 10th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 6.45. Nice day again spent most of the day worrying about trip to Bedford for dance on Thursday Mrs De Martin tried at first to organise a motor bus party but she appears to have failed. We thought of making enquiries about hiring cars and found we could get a 6 seater for 30/- Mrs Briggs has also found this out. But we must wait until Mrs de Martin speaks.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:soft-page-break/>Tuesday 11th February 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 6.0. Foggy morning but cleared to splendid day afterwards.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Wednesday 12th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By why at 6.30. Foggy day again clearing afterwards. Yesterday we arranged to go to by motor bus to Bedford or at least Mrs De Martin did. It was yesterday all so that the papers told us that Capt Scott the Antarctic explorer had been lost with five of his companions when returning from his dash to the Pole. He had reached the pole on Jan 18 1912 one month after Amundsen a Swede had reached it for the first time. He encounted various misfortunes &amp; unexpected bad weather on his return. He died eleven miles from a food depot &amp; was not found till 6 months afterwards when his body with that of Dr Wilson and Lient Barrous were found in the tent It makes a extraordinary thrilling tale and throws to uselessnes &amp; enacious selfishness of most of our lives in strong relief. The others two of the party had died before Petty Ofc Evans first and Capt Oates after the latter fell ill and practically died by his own hands to relieve his comrades.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Thursday 13th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 10.0 in view of the Bedford dance in the evening I did not go back to in the afternoon had a bit of a walk before tea Robottham and and I went down to the brewery house at six and there joined the Briggs party in the motor bus we had hired. Went over comfortably had a very good time at the dance. The costumes did not compare with the R.C.A fancy dress I went to. They had some newfangled dances in the middle of the programme but Marjorie and I sat there out in a cosy nook I discovered; she went as a cowgirl. Short skirt large hat and looked splendid. We got back at three. R &amp; I going up to the Hatton Park in the bus with Marjorie.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Friday 14th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By why at 10.0 I got a most mysterious card by post It is St Valentines day. It was addressed to the brewery and a picture entitled &quot;A gay dog from Stroud Green&quot; I know no one in that this direction can&apos;t make it out at all. Spent evening in the Briggs there was quite a large party there got to bed at about 1.0</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Saturday 15th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Very good show in the including St George Alexander Tea in RCA common room changed there for dance found I had bought old pumps with me, so had to buy another pair. Had a jolly time at the dance it was the little fancy dress. Struck with one fellow fancy dress. ample but defective Arab costume Dari had a rotten time she did not dance with any fellow but me. She was especially upset because one fellow permanent to with looked at dance with her and then had it with another she was so upset and fact that it set me thinking about the relative charms of her after &amp; this fellow home by the 12.05.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Sunday 16th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"><text:soft-page-break/>Cathedral at 1030 <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I16961&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged&amp;tab=0" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Will Pettit</text:a> and <text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.marlton.co.uk/genealogy/individual.php?pid=I16963&amp;ged=marlton-hurlin.ged" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">Isabel</text:a> came to tea his ship is refitting </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Monday 17th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Walked to Chatham with father in morning Isabel came in about 12.0 &amp; stopped some time</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P26" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 23rd <text:s/>1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">While we were at breakfast news was brought to Miss Humphrey that Mr Amos Edwards, Marjories father died at 3 o&apos;clock he has been suffering from chronic astham for two years he was about 75 church at 11.0 Sprake to tea</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P52" text:outline-level="4">Monday 24th Feb 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Bry at 6.0 Still cold fine Wrote to Aunt Jennie saying I would go down there next week if convienient Rowbotham showed me a letter from his old friend Newman who has apparently been trying to heal the engagment with the help of his fiancee Nellie. He advised Rowbotham to write to Frances Hewson &amp; try &amp; arrange a meeting.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Thursday 27th February 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Bry at 10.0 Mr Edwards funeral today at 2.0. I watched the procession from the painters store there was a large number of mourners. Institute in evening saw a Billiard match.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Saturday 3rd May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">by at 7.0. Had to rest my foot so could not go out in afternoon Rain.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Sunday 4th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">Church at 11.0.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Monday 5th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">by at 7.0 Fine morning wet evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Tuesday 6th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">by at 6.0 fine morning wet evening again.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Wednesday 7th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">bry at 6.0 Sprake returned in afternoon. Mrs Humphrey leaves Mrs Balaam today at latter&apos;s request she is going to stay with Mrs Edwards at Rosland.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Sunday 8th <text:s/>1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">By at 7.0. Nottingham by 10.0 train took a week end ticket ( Sat to Mondy ) night through to Nottm (6/6) Stopped in same train right through long waits at kettering &amp; leicester Nottm 12.23. Walked <text:soft-page-break/>through slums to Victoria station &amp; caught 1.8 to Bestwood found on arrival that Dorrathy had come down by same train.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Friday 9th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">brewery at 6.0 Nasty dull &amp; wet morning. The fine weather we were having a week ago has quite left us out has turned wet again. No county cricket has been possible yet owing to the wet state of the grounds. Dorrie arrived to dinner. Came to brewery to tea &amp; so did Mrs Sprake.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 10th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">by at 5.0 Mash. Damp and dull again. Last night I got a letter from Kibble of Brandon&apos;s telling me that the post of 3rd Young&apos;s Daniels job -- was going for £150 I wrote thanking him &amp; applied for the post. I also wrote Patterson went to Northampton in afternoon with had looked at churches and market came back on 7.35 with Marjorie E.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P54"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P54">Sunday 11th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Church 8.0 &amp; 11.0 Dinners and tea with Sprakes walk in afternoon Fine day</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Monday 12th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Nice morning wet in afternoon. Went by invitation to Edwards in morning met Mrs Edwards for first time. Stayed in afternoon evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Tuesday 13th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Walked to Finedon in morning to see about feathers, Beautiful hot day. Rest in afternoon, pleasant spin on river in evening went to exchange in evening Miss B. Rowbotham Marjorie E &amp; I very Hot Dorrie fainted very unfortunate.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 14th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Beautiful day again; By at 6.30. <text:s/>Dorrie left at 10.0 I left her ticket. Got reply from Wandsworth &amp; I wrote asking them to see me on Saturday also wrote to Mr H Holland for a testimonial.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P55" text:outline-level="4">Thursday 15th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Dull morning Rode to Moulton. Changed to splendid afternoon. Got a reply from Wandsworth saying would see me Saturday.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4"><text:soft-page-break/>Friday 16th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">bry at 6.0 fine day.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 17th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">London by 10.0 train Sat to Monday ticket 7 H? Left my bag at Charing X District to E Putney walked to Wandsworth. Saw Hitch, nice brewery had short interview with him he reminded me some what to Mr Holland looked in on Dickenson. He will shortly be alone again. Home by 2.35. Hot fine day. Had a little tennis in the evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P55" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 18th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Auntie Bessie Reid at home she is in a very bad state of health Nice morning turning wet later. brows came in in the evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P55" text:outline-level="4">Monday 19th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">London by 1.40 Met Dorrie at the Academy Not a remarkably good show Mary examples of RCA work in the Black &amp; White &amp; Modelling. Tea at Popular cafe&apos; Caught 6.30 at St P. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P51">Tuesday 20th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">by at 10.0 busy all day.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P56" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 21st May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P57">by at 6.30 cooler and dull</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P57"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P53" text:outline-level="4">Thursday 22nd May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">by at 10.0 Glorious day and a splendid afternoon&apos;s tennis playing with much more confidence than last year.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P56" text:outline-level="4">Friday 23rd May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">by at 6.0 fine day and evening on the river with Mr and Mrs Sprake.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P56" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 24th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10 Very hot Played tennis at Briggs in afternoon. Got a letter from youngs saying they could not offer me the post. Yesterday morning I had a letter from Hammonds Bradford By in answer to a <text:soft-page-break/>reply I sent to an advertisement in the Brewers Journal. I told them I wanted one £180 unless they had Maltings.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P58" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 25th May 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P59">Church at 11.0 Very hot again. Tea at Sprakes walking evening London temperature 77°.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Monday 26th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 <text:s/>By at 6.0 Very hot again took to summer clothing. Tennis in evening played a feeble game but with Mrs Doudall <text:s/>beat Jack Barnes &amp; Miss Curtis Lond temp 80°</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Tuesday 27th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0 Still very hot Thunderstorm in afternoon with heavy hail storm Stones as large as marbles. Had wiff ? out on the river in the evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wednesday 28th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.15 Fine again. Tennis in evening. Felt very energetic and went for a 6 mile walk in dash ? after supper.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Thursday 29th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0 Very close tennis in aftern could not play at all. Heavy rain for 1/2 hour at 4 o&apos;clock Finer later.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Friday 30th May 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 Very hot again. Heard from Dorie that after Athur Allen&apos;s father has died this is very sad indeed and will no doubt alter their plans. Short ride in evening find but windy.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Saturday 31st May</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10 unsettled day with rain at noon but as I had arranged to go to Bedford I set off about 2.30 I had a headwind but I escaped the rain and got there at 4.30 Wallace introduced me to the two friends he had palled up with the Duncan &amp; Bishop we had tea at the place I have been to before and then got into a punt had a very pleasant evening and stayed listening to the band till after 10 I then found that I could not train home until 1.27 so decided to ride Wallace lent me his lamp it was a beautiful night but I dash I got in at 1.0.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Sunday 1st June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Church at 11.0 Had a few words with Marjorie. Walk with Sprake in afternoon and she there left about six and went up to Roseland under pretence of returning a pattern crochet to Miss Humphrey. found Marjorie alone in the house this is not exactly what I expected or wanted but I&apos;ve hung about in the garden till Mrs E &amp; the others returned from church; they set off for a walk so I went home beautiful day without being hot</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Monday 2nd June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 6.30 Beautiful day again. Tennis in evening</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Tuesday 3rd June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 8.0 Fine again rode over to Denford in evening I had us run on the River there very pleasant river is straighter and broader than here but the nearest shore</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wednesday 4th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Bry at 6.0 Splendid morning . We are really having beautiful weather just now it has been fine almost every day since the 11th May and although it got very sultry early past of the past week SW winds have made milder is Friday tennis in evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Thursday 5th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0 Tennis in afternoon it rained about 3 soon cleared up began</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Friday 6th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">be why at six got a letter from Hitch saying that the man they had decided on could not come and asking for my references. by the same post came a note from Wootton telling me of the job stormy rainy day spent evening in brewery.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Sunday 8th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Early service at 11.0 had a few words with M.E. Sprakes to tea and walk afterwards</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Monday 9th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 630 Sprakes had enquiry from Hitch about me and replied in glowing terms. Tennis in evening</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Tuesday 10th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 10.0 spent most of days scraping scale from the copper lined F.V. tennis in evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wednesday 11th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0. Letter from Hitch saying I had the job at Wandsworth &amp; telling me to go up tomorrow. dullday in evening went for a long ride to Naseby. Had a particularly head wind there are so that it took me two hours &amp; 10 min to do the 19 miles to the village. Pass through CottesbBrooke a pretty village and will win, large house. Most of the road passed over private fields and these were gates which delayed me have blocked the road also was very rough</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Sunday 22nd June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61"><draw:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.carlparsons.com/Georgeparsons/uploads/GMP005.jpg" office:name="George Parsons"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr2" draw:name="Image3" text:anchor-type="char" svg:width="9.71cm" svg:height="6.793cm" draw:z-index="2"><draw:image draw:mime-type="image/jpeg">
