   <text:p text:style-name="P62">George Parsons rowing </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P62">Marjorie Edwards and </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P62">Mrs Sprake </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P62">Kempston, </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P62"><text:soft-page-break/>Photo taken by Mr Sprake</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Breakfast with Mrs Balaam&apos;s cousin from Chicago. She can talk. Church at 11.0 M. E was there Tea with Sprakes took some photos. walk afterwards. then I went onto Edwards to show them their River photos Mrs Edwards and M were at home. Miss Humphrey turned up soon afterwards and I helped water the garden. I then had some time with Marjorie alone and we wandered about. I didn&apos;t know what to say to her and she seemed awkward too. on Thursday I had told her how fond I had grown <text:span text:style-name="T50">of</text:span> her during the short time I had known her and she admitted a liking for me, I now want to tell her more. I took her into the hall and there I told her I loved her I could not speak coherently or clearly but I tried to explain to her that I thought we ought to wait until we had separated a while before we made any promises to each other, she said she agreed but I was not sure she really did. I star<text:span text:style-name="T50">yed</text:span> to supper and we went for a walk afterwards <text:span text:style-name="T50">with </text:span>the whole family but they soon turned back and left us to go on alone. We did and stopped by a gate where we had another long talk. I found things easier out there in the open are on such a splendid night and we cling together by the gate how stupid it has seems to write it all and now we told each other of our love I told her how my affection had grown. how I had so often gone out of my way to meet and how I had majored in Sunday&apos;s best she might come to tea with Miss Humphrey. We talked and talked and works supremely happy at least I was and I think she was too. At last we turned homewards. I told her that I have spoken of my love rather than go away without saying anything and asked her if she was disappointed in me that I had not wished to find ourselves at once she said she agreed that we were better as we were b<text:span text:style-name="T50">ut</text:span> must ask her mother to let me keep in touch with her when she had gone. This I promise to do I took her back to her house but we found it very difficult part at last I<text:span text:style-name="T50">`ve</text:span> arranged to have tea with her in Northampton the next day and she went <text:span text:style-name="T50">there</text:span> I felt so happy she seemed to love me so much more that I felt I deserved and she seemed to take my plan so sensibly. I do hope that I am doing right I can&apos;t think that it would be wise to make a promise me as anything yet I don&apos;t really feel use of myself and yet it seems impossible that I will never cease to love her. She&apos;s it is all that a man can possibly desire beautiful figure and face with a soul behind it nothing foolish or frivolous and yet most refreshing sense of humour. Miss skillets until July yes the old Latin tag fits Spendidley. I felt satisfied that we had come to understand each other. We must part for all little while and as I told her we will soon know if our love has anything classing it or whether costs we are merely under the influence of passing infatuation, yet I know it will be very difficult to keep faithful to each other when we are apart. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Monday 23rd June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.30. Saw M. At breakfast time and went to station with her very prosaic ride to Northampton in afternoon met her for and click activity to one Oriental cafe</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Tuesday 25th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 5.30. Printed photos all day tennis in evening small attendance but got some good games</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wednesday 26th June 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 10.0. Wrote home tennis in afternoon went out to Roseland after tea and had an enjoyable time played tennis with Phil against May and Kath singles with Marj. She had a very good idea though i<text:span text:style-name="T50">t </text:span>of course <text:span text:style-name="T50">would</text:span> want some practice. I had supper with their help Was some algebra and found to my horror that I knew nothing about quadratic equations. Had some time with Marjorie in the <text:soft-page-break/>garden getting things in she does seems so terribly fond of me it makes afraid I do fervently hope that that the fears I have <text:span text:style-name="T50">for </text:span>my affection may be groundless. I had a short talk with Mrs Edwards I asked her if I she should would let me write to Marjorie when I left she wanted to know if I really cared for her and assured her I did before we ought to going it to go get no further at present she umphatically agreed in that she told me she knew in the winter that M was very.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Thursday 21st August 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">More in papers about this &quot;Plague&quot;. I am myself very uneasy about i<text:span text:style-name="T50">t </text:span>in the view of my one to clean life in the <text:s/>passed &amp; it worried me all day. By at 9.15. Beautiful day. Had been to bathe in <text:s/>lueensmere before breakfast had a splendid time. <text:span text:style-name="T50">in</text:span> evening went up to S.K with the idea of visiting the exhibition of the Royal Collage but found it had closed last week. Dorrie had a piece of needlwork <text:s/>these which had evoked an enquiry from the some lady enthusiast Went to Sloane Square &amp; bought a folding camera at the City Sale &amp; Exchange for £1-18-6 which would be worth I find £2-17-6. I will see what I can make of it. Went back to brewery &amp; entered for Mr Hitch.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 22nd August 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 6.0 fine day still worrying about the state of my body, so much so that I made up my mind to go &amp; see a doctor I went to Dr Carmichael he told me that my experience was that of by far the larger majority of men &amp; gave me much advice. I was very glad I went there was an and unpeasants subject.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 23rd August 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">by at 9.0 left for home at 10:30 court 11.43 at 11 11. found both mother and father very well Mr hitch had said I ought to have a holiday. I&apos;d talk to them about it and we decided to go to Ostend next Friday. Took some photos with the new camera which we were very successful showery day.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 24th August 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Cathedral at 10:30 service in the nave. More showers. Letter from Dorie from Gib.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Monday 25th August 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">left at 7:45 glorious day letter from Dorie awaited me from London &amp; usual one from Marjorie sweet soul.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 20th September 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Wretched damp morning. By 6.0. Home G 11.40 H.H. Developed photo of holiday.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 21th September 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Fine day Cathedral at 10.30 Brous <text:s/>came in in evening I learnt that he proposed to come to London in March &amp; we discussed amalgamating.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Mon 22th September 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Up G 7.47 Nice day. Letter from Majorie Daniell invited me to join a hockey club &amp; I said I would. Had rotten headache.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Mon 23rd September 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">By at 6.0 Electrical treatment in evening 3rd sitting.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Wed 1st October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Ram Brewery, Wandsworth</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:s text:c="4"/>I now start a new book, on a most suitable day, and at the same time I started trial of a new system. <text:s/>I have come to the conclusion that&apos;s my previous system of keeping a diary has been a bit of failure. <text:s/>It has not been worth reading again for any interest attaches to it and the facts and mind doing so in most difficult to trace. <text:s/>For many weeks at the time it has contain nothing but just notes of into most trivial a passing importance.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:s text:c="4"/>I now proposes to keep two pages going at once. On the left by propose to make notes of firstly, the weather is this is a subject which always provides valuable matter for reference and also jottings of my doings etc. <text:s/>On the right I intend to rights of the most important of the latter in the former form and also any remarks about There are other things in which I am interested. <text:s/>I will soon see how the new plan X. <text:s/>Greater stability I have to fear is my own slackness for this sort of thing should be kept always going and not just left to one feels inclined for at I think have a that the new system will be will lend itself more readily to compromising with occasional</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:s text:c="4"/>The chief of end of these first days of October was the starting of happy. <text:s/>Danielle is a member of the mid Surrey and Ealing club <text:s/>was at one time Secretary. He asked me if I would care to join the and although I know that this sort of thing is not my strong point I consented, <text:s/>because I think that the exact size will do me a lot of good and I thought to have opportunities of mixing with other young fellows. <text:s/>Last Saturday I went down to the ground and with Danielle and watched the trial game and on Monday because the: asking me to play for the 4 team this Saturday. This wasn&apos;t afterwards <text:s/>altered </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 4th October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">as a team could not be raised. So I played for the 3rd against the Spencer Club from Wimbledon. I felt very much a sea but I will no doubt get into it. After the game I got back to Wandsworth took the 7.0 train home </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 4th Oct 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">by at 5:30 beautiful day cold morning went to sywell in afternoon whist drive in</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:soft-page-break/>Mon 6th October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Monday night I came up on the early train with Grace Wyles and Miss. Smitham and another new student at the RCA Miss Wyles said Dorrie had not written a word to her since she left England. In the evening I made up my mind with regard to music lessons . I had been to see Mr. Weston, 59 west hill, one day last week bodies terms were 2 1/2 guineas so around him that I could not take this, and enquired of Mr. Saunders, Geraldine Rd. His proved to be 2 g. <text:s/>Meanwhile Weston wrote he would take me for 2 g Mrs. Hall then pointed out an advert in the paper of Mr. Dean 46 southfields Rd, 12 lessons for 10/6. I went to see him on Monday night and I fixed up with him for 9 - 10 PMon Mondays. he is a hamble person who apparently spends his time Tuning pianos though Mrs Hall tells me he is a school teacher and has a great reputation. <text:s/>I find the my fingers are terribly stiff <text:s/>and even simple exercises have to start on seem extraordinary difficult. I propose to practice after breakfast for 40 min and after dinner for 30. I ought Ought to be able to get rather more time than this and so make one of hours a day though I don&apos;t think there will be able to manage more.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Tues 7th October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Tuesday I went up in the evening to the Sir John Cass technical institutes, Jewry St Aldgate for the first time I&apos;m taking up two lectures a week brewery and Malting in Building on Tuesday and Micro Biology on Friday. We started with a very interesting lecture on the barley corn.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">When I got back I found a letter from Dorrie the waiting <text:s/>me. <text:s/>They have taken rooms in Alexandria and she is housekeeping the had no servants but a bedouin comes in to clean for them.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 18th October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P63"><text:s text:c="4"/>On Saturday in the morning papers had the news of the destruction by fire the latest German Zepplin with the loss of 28 lives making it the fourth disaster of the week. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P63"><text:s text:c="3"/>I left for Wellingborough by the 10.5 from St.P. <text:s/>on Saturday morning and getting to wellingborough went straight to the brewery. <text:s/>Taking them all by the horns, so to speak, I went to see the Brigg&apos;s before going with Sprake to dinner. We had a splendid day and in the afternoon Sprake and I went for a walk; I had previously been to see Mrs. Balaam &amp; Rowbotham. He is there alone now has my successor behaved in such a rakish a manner that Mrs. Balaam had to get rid of him. It 8 o&apos;clock I went up to Roseland but as they told me that my it would be expecting me to meet her I went out again and once and walks down with Kath; She left me outside the shop and I MX Marjorie in the churchyard had thought all this out before and had come to the conclusion that I would be much that if I waited for her roles and for one thing I felt rather doubtful about my reception he was the it was the first meeting since passing after our first glorious fortnight together, we had been Apart 3 months and I was not at all certain that I had the same position as before. <text:s/>Going to meet her would I thought by taking too much for granted so I decide on the safer plan. <text:s/>I found however that she must be unmistakably looking forward to seeing me and so I went to meet her. <text:s/>We met as I said in the churchyard where we had so often met before on one pretext for another; I did not know what to do exactly, but we shook hands in us give proper fashion allowed to <text:soft-page-break/>drive her back I found I had quite misguided or she was exactly the same as were there for and we&apos;ve dropped at once into a old relationship without paying more moment of awkwardness. <text:s/>We had a little while together after suburb of time when centre by quickly and it was past 10.00 in no time she came out with me to &quot;shut the gate&quot; <text:s/>And that took some time. <text:s/>By got back to Mrs. Sprake had gone to bed.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sun 19th October 1913</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P63">On Sunday morning we went to the 11. O&apos;clock High Mass at St Barnabas and a very high it was too.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Diary">We Had a look round the brewery before dinner and after dinner went for a walk with Mr. and Mrs. Sprake, it was a splendid afternoon. I went to &quot;Roseland&quot; at 4 O&apos;clock. It was Mrs. Edwards birth wedding day and Phil&apos;s birthday. (12 I think). After tea Marjorie &amp; I went for a walk Mrs. Edwards would not come. <text:s/>We went up to Hardwick road to a gate which had played an important part with us before we spent some time up there Lunch we wanted to be back at 7.0 Mrs. Edwards was not feeling well and we thought it only right that we should go back. <text:s/>Before we went in however I told Marjorie of my meeting with the little girl in Ostend. At she was very annoyed I think she was feeling deeply hurt and I thought that I had really &quot;done it&quot;. We hardly said a word for the last half mile there wasn&apos;t going to let her go in like that. I told her how lonely I had been there and asked her to forgive me eyebrows and I vowed that I would never have anything to do with any while I had her &amp; This vow <text:s/>I pray God that I may keep. Eventually she said she forgave me &amp; was glad that I had told her. The rest of the evening we sat side by side trimming photographs and chatting with Mrs. Edwards. We have a little time to our selves after supper &amp; I felt that the little incident about the ostend modest had cleared the air.She was all so good to me &amp; I felt thoroughly ashamed of myself for betraying a complete trust in me. I hope I may never do so again. I left at 10.0 though it wasn&apos;t bit of a struggle, but Mrs. Edwards I knew was not feeling fit to sit up and any longer. <text:s/>Marjorie came to the Gate as before. This Sprakes were surprised to see me &amp; had made up of the fire expecting me about the- 11.0. <text:s/>We sat up talking Till I found with a start that it was nearly twelve.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Mon 20th October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Sprake called me and 6.30 on Monday morning. we left the house At 7.30 to catch the 8.0 train. Margorie me us at Broad Green &amp; Sprake left us outside the &quot;Hind&quot;. It was unfortunate in some ways that Mr W. Ashdown was at the station for he is a bank for one thing &amp; also has a silly &amp; talkative wife so I suppose the news will be all over the town and that Marjorie saw me off. <text:s/>We parted with the understanding that I would be down again before Christmas. <text:s/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:s/>I had a glorious week end and favoured with most beautiful weather. Marjorie was sweeter than ever because we got more &amp; more natural with each other.I have been asking her whether she is in love with me for with the idea of being in love &amp; She always affirms that the latter has nothing whatsoever to do with it . <text:s/>I flatter myself that she is telling the truth in any case I can&apos;t think that anything can separate us now. This Sprakes were all for good. They had kept telling me to do exactly as I might about stopping with them </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60"><text:soft-page-break/>Tues 21st October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wed 22nd October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Thur 23rd October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Fri 24th October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Friday night we had thick fog, the buses were all delayed so returning from the Sir John Cass I came by District. That was quite disorganised &amp; I only got as far as Putney Bridge. It was very weird walking over the iron bridge he could not see the lamps until about 20 ft from them. On the other side also ideal ask myself by taking the wrong turning. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Saturday 25th October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">on Saturday I went to Richmond to play hockey and found the younger Norman (Wellingboro&apos;) there playing for Richmond 2nd he recognised me but could not place me.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Sunday 26th October 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">on Sunday I went to lunch with Mr Hitch &amp; met Mrs Hitch for the first time. I thought her very nice indeed and I enjoyed it very much. Their little kiddie Joyce is a sweet little thing too.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">That evening I went over to the Alton&apos;s at Chiswick I had not been there since just after I came to London. I had imagined that Rowena was rather too nice to me, she certainly seemed cold at this time.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60">Wedesday 5th November 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Wednesday morning I had a card from Sprake to say he would be down at the brewery in the morning but could not have lunch with me as I wanted to. He was going to Thomsons Stockwell he got down about a 11:45 had hasty look round I saw him to his bus. I left the brewery about 1.0 had lunch at regions and got to the show just before 3. Almost directly I got inside I ran into Patterson &amp; Greenstreet. I spent some time with them and then went on to halons stand and found the Sprague. We went round together but saw very little. We went out and had some tea together and then went back to the show till 6.45 by this time I felt decidedly mighty I had to leave them and rushed off to the OBG dinner at the Holborn. I got there in time for the fish. I found Daniell , with Kibble and Wootton opposite, I did not however speak to Carl. Things got interesting at the end of the dinner Finch, the chairman, gave a brief account of what had been done by the OBG with regards to the examination seeing but forward by the Institute of brewing. Delegates of the two books had met: A man from Lancashire got up and said that their section had been kept in the dark about this and although there have sent a delegate the views he expressed were not those of the majority of the Lancashire section they were strongly opposed to the sounds he reached dealt most admirably with matter he said that the Lancashire section have been treated inexact in the same way as the others. Other men voiced opposition views but the majority were clearly on Finch&apos;s side and went our London chairman got our for the opposition he was greeted with derisive laughter. He had obviously been to the show. I went back home with Kibble and we spoke of me joining in with his <text:soft-page-break/>yacht next year. I would like to be very much but as I got home once a fortnight fancy that I will have much time for it.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P64">Thursday 9th November 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">on Sunday I intended to go over to Beckenham but it was a wet and wretched that I decided not to and spent the evening in my rooms I found plenty</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P66"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P66">25th December 1913</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">On Christmas morning Mother &amp; I went to St Margarets at 8. There was a very good congregation At breakfast we had the usual distribution of gifts Mother &amp; Father gave me a nice little sovereign purse &amp; Auntie an OR Scarf. I Went to the Cathederal at 10.30 It was a glorious day, cold &amp; clear. We lit the pudding according to the custom &amp; drank to Dorrie ( &amp; Margorie )</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P66"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thurs 1st January 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">On thurs I went to Fulham to look up the Walgates &amp; found them entertaining a new year partyspent a pleasant evening there.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P66"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Fri 2nd January 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">On Friday morning Leonard Wallis rang me up &amp; came down to see me in the afternoon. He has had a bad run of luck. He left Bedford for a job at Willesdon but 3 weeks after the move the firm went bankrupt so he is now out of a berth. About the same time he found that he had ruptured himself and now waring a truss. I showed him around the brewery &amp; then we went up to the Victoria Palace house vary good show.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P66"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Fri 4th January 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">On Sunday I went down to Ada&apos;s. She was alone Tom being down at Bristol</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thur 6th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">On Thursday I arranged myself in my tail coat &amp; went down to Adas to Whist party Capt &amp; Mrs Pilkington were there and Mrs Green with her son &amp; daughter, latter seemed a nice girl and Sang well though with some afflectation. Had a very good evening I had the luck to get highest score though as a matter of fact I believe that Ada had a higher one still.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65">I found myself making comparisons between Eirene green and Marjorie perhaps it was only natural on the eve of M momentous visit. I sing though that M can hold her own in spite of the fact that she pretends neither to play nor the same for in all else she is perfect and if she had time I have no doubt she could play as well as anyone.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P65"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 7th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">Marjorie and Mrs Edwards came up today</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">it turned out a wretched day being unable to get away from the brewery as soon as I should have only just got to St Pancras in time; the up train being quite punctual. We made straight for Holborn through the rain and left our bags there and then we went on to St Pauls. We spent about half an hour there then went on to Evans and had some lunch after lunch we made for the tower. It was just after finding it impossible to get us we walked. It was very much the picture is only an hour to do the tower so then I suggested that Houses of Parliament. We were however unlucky in defining the House of Commons closed . It was so wretched that it seemed useless staying any longer in town so I decided to catch the 4:15 we went up to Holborn on top of a bus and had 17 next to the station it was too foggy going down to see anything much. Saturday evening we spent quite pleasantly playing cards Marjorie went out with me down to the highest Street art the supper we got a note from well to say that they would not be able to: the morrow as Isabel was in bed perhaps with Appendicitis. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sun 8th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">Sunday again started wet Marjorie and I went to the Cathedral at 8.9 Mrs Edwards went with us again at 10:30 we went out for a walk before dinner but it was too rough to be pleasant. The mornings post brought the unwelcome news that Isabel had indeed got appendicitis I had been taken to a nursing home on sat night for an operation. We&apos;ll came in just before we went to the Cathedral and told us that she had been operated on and once and was now going on well.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">In the afternoon I took Marjorie up to my room and we talked about many things including mother that she said only in creased her love. I gave her the ring I had got; she put it on.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">So far things have gone well enough but fate was up against us with the bad weather and Isabel&apos;s illness. We&apos;ll came into the tea but depression I had settled over me I can&apos;t for the life of me say now why I did not tell him that we were engaged. So start the ball rolling so to speak. It might have been in nature reticence but I think I&apos;d rather meeting the girl at aiders on Thursday had made me only too obvious of Marjorie shortcomings things are however now gave to for the draw which back and there have moreover back of my mind and firm conviction that he stack evening in my love was merely transitionary. We&apos;ll left early and the evening dragged along till Rouse turned up and supper time meanwhile Mrs Edwards enliven things and lids by playing some of the college songs</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Mon 9th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">The crowning disaster was that the Monday opened wet &amp; got worse. Grace Whyles looked in with news from Miss curling sending Dorrie.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">Wakes broad Eastgate house and also the Cathedral but could do nothing else. The rain came down in sheets all of the afternoon we sat in drawing-room but my depression had I think increased and <text:soft-page-break/>mother was in a bad mood. We left by the 4:23 train and I think that neither Marjorie or Mrs Edwards test mother when they left. We went by underground from Cannon Street to St Pancras to avoid the rain had 20 min to spare.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">Look back in the week and I must confess that it seemed a terribly disastrous one I do not know yet that mother and file thought of Marjorie but it seems quite certain that she and Mrs Edwards and mother to much for them. I felt wretched when I looked back upon it and all my love seem to have gone &amp; I looked back upon our acquaintance as a continuous of serve indulgence can it be that my love is really dead? I pray to God it may not be so. It is unthinkable if so I have been a terrible fall all along and have dealt most shamefully with Marjorie No! I think that it is passing depression and that my love will soon return with all its old strength.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">I went to the Institute of Brewery meeting a lot read a paper compiled in conjunction with Carl Wootton they told us nothing new Carles was part consisted in manipulating blackboards though I believe he had gone round to various breweries in search of data. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Tues 10th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">On Tuesday I awoke with a bad sore throat did not help me in shaking off my sorrowfull mood. As if Tim Mock asked whether turned out fine though in the afternoon we got some snow </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thurs 19th March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67">On Thursday evening I spent the evening with the Dickinson&apos;s at their new house 54, Clarendon Rd. Putney putting pictures up.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sat 21st March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69">On Saturday I received three watercolour sketches from Arthur for the Academy. It was too wet for hockey &amp; the match was scratched I took the sketches over to Walgate to get them framed as my man in Wandsworth appeared to be bankrupt Walkergate knew a good place &amp; we took them there. It seemed that Mrs Walgate was expecting a new arrival caught the 4:15 at Victoria.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sun 22nd March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69">On Sunday I went to the Cathedral in the morning Brous. He told me he had got a motorcycle &amp; had written it down from Blackheath the day before disappointed that will had not come in.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Mon 23rd March 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69"><text:soft-page-break/>on Monday evening we had an unusual mishap in the brewery. We were brewing stout . When we came to turnouts the second copper we found that the foul had broken &amp; would not open.. I suggested trying to siphon it out with a fire hose but Hitch thought this would be dangerous. Finally we got to work with a hand pump &amp; and pumped it out much time was taken however by renewing the leathers as these kept going. Hydraulic leathers buckets were the only thing that would hold at all on the Valves. I was on duty &amp; did not get to bed till 2. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Monday 4th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69">I got a letter from Dorrie on Monday telling me they had the news; they knew weeks ago.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Tuesday 5th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69"><text:s/>Marjorie&apos;s letter was sorrowful she had as I say been to the dentist and it appears that Mrs E benefit from the business will be very small. I believe that they are basing per share on the profits for the past year and every fresh piece of news seemed to make the outlook worse. Their house has been let and they are now looking for another. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P69">Sir John Cass in evening.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 8th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Another letter which I got on Friday was more depressing still. In this Marjorie said she might have to leave Northampton because her mother would not be able to pay for her season. This of course seems incredible; as a matter of fact I would be very willing to pay for the ticket if they were really driven to this. She is in a serious position because she would bring in more if she stayed at home then she was at work. She has been trying to get a job in Wellingborough but can so far only get it chance of an offer as a second &quot;sales&quot;. This to me does not seem good enough unless there was us reasonable prospect of her soon getting a better post. Of course if she could get a job as head it would suit her down to the ground and do a lot of good, but perhaps she is too young. They have taken a house in Castle Street &quot;Homeleigh&quot; and are moving in after Whitsun. What annoyed me was hedges attitude he apparently benefits largely from their misfortune and now it appears he has the bare faced audacity is to suggest that Mrs Edwards should support herself by taking lodgers they have never said a word to me against him but on the face of it I cannot help thinking that he is not playing straight unfortunately both Mrs Edwards he have the same lawyer and so cannot see what else that you can have any certain that her interests are being properly looked after.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">On Friday afternoon I went to the Academy with Ada. Arthur&apos;s picture was on the bottom row over screen. The rest of the show was very ordinary with no picture that stood out at all.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 9th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Home by 2.0 train Went over to Strood in evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4"><text:soft-page-break/>Sunday 10th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Cathederal at 8 &amp; 10:30. Stayed in rest of day Brows came in in evening.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Monday 11th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">I was glad I went to the Institute of brewing on Monday the 11th for old Holland was up from Marlow it was the first time I&apos;d seen him since I had left.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"><text:s text:c="4"/>Summer came upon us with full force on Saturday Danielle was taking duty for the week end so I was free but Kibble went down to Maidenhead. I asked Wallis to share the dinghy with me and we have a spending afternoon together. On Sunday Kibble &amp; I got down to the soon after 11 engine was finished &amp; we put it on &amp; got the sales arms too; we had lunch in the boat Cragoe came down in the afternoon &amp; we sailed up to Thames Ditton &amp; had tea there. We came back on the engine, Cragoe left us &amp; Kibble &amp; I went out in the dinghy for a bit together back to the boat for supper. It was a perfect day and we had a glorious time there were a lot of people on the River and new lines of most of buses we were told that had brought them largest crowd on record to Hampton Court.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 20th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">On Wednesday Hitchcock have told of an unpleasant rumours to the effect that the city of London had bought up Stanfield&apos;s, of much tales have been about before but if this is true it is a most unfortunate thing for all of them over there and silly hope it&apos;s not. I went over there on Wed but they said nothing to me about it and I did not want to mention it for fear of giving them on and necessary scare.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thursday 21st May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">I have another splendid afternoon on River on Thursday. The Conservancy&apos;s Now passed the engine and Kibble has managed to patch the league cup sufficiently well with the cement we could not move the boat however because the accumulator had run down. We had supper there and decided to sleep in her on Saturday if Danielle can take early samples for me on Sunday.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P60"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 22nd May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Went up west in evening to look for &quot;Grumpy&quot; Had a splendid exhibition of lightening coming back</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">We had to abandon this however because the thunderstorm on Friday was followed by a wet and cold Saturday.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thursday 28th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P71">On Thursday in spite of the weather turning rather wet we took the boat up to little Halford. It was the first time I had been up this stretch of river and found it much more pretty than I expected although the bank of lined with water works there almost entirely hidden and there are many really pretty spots. We had tea just beyond tags Island supper when we got to Halford.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 29th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">Fulham in the evening to tennis.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">On Friday we got the news of the sinking of the lines Empress of Ireland after collision with the collier Storstad in the St Lawrence about 960 drowned and 450 saved. That collision occurred about 2:30 on Friday morning. The Empress of Ireland was steaming down the river through a slight mist. The collier was seen to miles of to port when bank of form blue in between. The liner stopped and gave warning to that effect by her foghorn but the collier went straight on &amp; caught her amidship tearing <text:s/>right down her side. She Sank in 10 minutes.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 30th May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">On Saturday I left the brewery just before 2 and took the bus to Charing X. I left my bag and rackets there &amp; got the to Euston in time to meet Marjorie as she came in by the 12.50. We took her bag to Charing X and then went straight to the Academy. We had tea there and then went for a short stroll down Piccadilly and Constitution Hill.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I took her to dinner at the Holborn felt rather at sea under the strange circumstances. Then we walked down to Charing X and got our tickets before we went to the theatre. We enjoyed grumpy very much indeed Cyril Maude was blended and she was very well supported and 40 I found I had lost one of the tickets when we got to Charing X. We went down and 11.40 got to bed just around about one o&apos;clock.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 31st May 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Whit Sunday</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">We were up for the 8 o&apos;clock service on Sunday we went to the Cathedral we went again at 10.30 also at 7 as it was a wet evening</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Monday 1st June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Monday we were early on the move. M and I got the tennis court marked out before breakfast and played a bit after. We started for a walk about 11.0. Going out Broom hill. From there we went on to Gads Hill coming back partly by ear. Any afternoon we went to see the Rhodedendrous in Cobham Park they were a lovely site and also had a glimpse of cobham village, but the whole place was swarming with &quot;masses&quot;. We went back by Cuxton. I was riding dads by and Marjorie Dorrie&apos;s. We found may Gardner and Gordon Avery waiting for us at home. We had some good tennis with them in the evening but beat them badly. I think we really did too much for one day five felt great time and I expect Marjorie did to though she did not own it.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">We caught the 7.45 at strood in the morning but it was 8.50 before it got to Cannon Street so we took the district to Charing X and change there to Hampstead. We got the Euston only just in time <text:soft-page-break/>for Ms&apos; train (9.20) leaving about 1/2 min to spare. I did not get to brewery till 10.15 Daniell was there then but left us to go home his daughter was born later in the day.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Thursday 4th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Thursday I went down to little forks that with cable and spent the afternoon sailing although it turned somewhat cold in the evening we stopped down there for the night. The cabin is various snipe weight is all covered in I did not have a very comfortable night. Strangeness may have been something to do with it or perhaps it was not warm enough. We came up by the 8.17 in the morning.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 7th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Sunday Daniell &amp; I started work on the proposed tennis lawn behind the brewery half of it can be brought along without any work but the rest we will have to double we will have to put it down 6&quot; at one corner. The Turf seems strong but under the surface mostly bricks with some good soil in places. The slowest if well Be getting the turf up. They will have to get out the bricks to some little that we made a good start by getting the levels playing up about to sq yards of turf.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">In the afternoon I went out in the dinghy with Wallis. Kibble being down at Bisley, if we had frequent showers, one in the evening when we were just above Molesey was followed by one of the most perfect double rainbows I have ever seen.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I found I caught a bad cold seeping down in the boat on Thursday and returned to winter shirts. The weather has indeed turned quite cold again</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 13th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Saturday I cycled home. The roads all the way were good and had been altered somewhat; especially just beyond Eltham where what used to be a hedge lined Lane has been turned into a broader road with ride paths and a severe iron railing.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I did not have a pleasant ride as the wind was strong and dead ahead.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 14th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Sunday I escaped but terrible thunderstorm that centred over Wandsworth. Six people were killed by lightning on Wandsworth Common and two died later while the rain was so heavy as to cause floods in several places and two of our publicans cellers were flooded in Rochester we had no sign of it</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">As a result of discussions at home much deliberation on my part I wrote to Marjorie asking her if she would like to go for our holiday to Ostend I wrote to Mrs Edwards at the same time I got favourable replies are both so that is settled and we start on July 10</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"><text:soft-page-break/>I left the brewery in a troubled state on Friday and went down to Shepperton with Kibble by the 2.55 from Putney. A thunderstorm met us so after hanging about in this station is sometime we adjourned to a pub for tea. Eventually we got away at 5.30 but our troubles were not over but the accumulators broke down we eventually reached Staines soon after 8.0 and stayed there For the night at a boathouse at the backwater. Before turning in we have walk around and took the accumulators to the power station to be charged. They did not really undertake this sort of work but fortunately we found the chief of the shop and he took a great interest in the job and put them on all night. As it proved it was the most succesful recharge we have all the time</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 20th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">On Saturday we were up at 6.45 . We had neither slept very well and them morning was dull, we had a bath and got of about 10. We made a short stop at Datchet to get some petrol and reach Windsor at 12.0 . We anchored just above Boveney for lunch and the weather had of them quite okayd up. We found the stream so strong that we could make but for progress and did not reach Born end till well after 4. We had tea there and did a bit of sailing but as rain was threat Anyway we pushed on to Marlow it was regatta day there and we came in just at the end. I did some shopping and after supper we watch the fireworks. We moored for the night on the cement wall just above Bisham a very good spot as it turned out</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Sunday 21th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Sunday morning we were awakened by a shower at 6.0 we got up and got away before nine though whether gradually cleared. We had lunch just beyond sinning bit when we got past Pangbourne we came into a heavy shower I returned to the In and cable took her on through it. We had tea when it stopped and eventually got to Wallingford about 7.0 Arcturus record run for the boat of 34 miles.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Wallingford I thought a charming spot we took a look round the town and saw them brewery &amp; Roman earthworks. We moored just below the old block an ideal spot</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Monday 22th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Next morning we did some shopping &amp; Got going about 11 at Benson lock we were startled by a pretty girl falling in their she put to little boys ashore she was however in the shallow water and will soon pulled out by a lady with her and taken to the lock house, of them more anon. The day was fine but not warm. We had tea at 5 after Iffley lock. We pushed through Oxford moored below Medley weir about 7. I went up into the town for letters leaving Kibble to have his supper he was out when I got back from mine. I wrote to Marjorie. We had some rain that evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Tuesday 23rd June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">We got through the we are about 9:30 they called up the we&apos;re boards making the drop of about a foot in this case into a torrent and the boat has to steam up it. I helped with the line but she nearly did it herself Kings weir the next one is a much bigger affair but we did that alright and also the smaller Smaller one an Eynsham, where I took some photos. There is another at Harts. We had <text:soft-page-break/>lunch just beyond Evesham tea at 10ft bridge where we fell in with a party of girls who we towed up to Tadpole. We stopped at radical rage a charming spot at 8. We walked into Cranfield a charming village &amp; after a drink at the Swan where all work drunk we turned in.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 24th June 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">We got away at 9.15. That&apos;s morning I did not buy a I strained my back again the day before and thought it wise not to go and get up to lechdale and on the Round House at Inglesham here we found the seven Canal disused and out of repair we were told that the river was good up to Ransford but Kibble was nervous lest the boat might get stranded by the water going down. We have a look round lechdale but I got little pleasure out of it as my back was very painful having given </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Tuesday 28th Jul 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Collision between the nationalist volunteers in Dublin and the police and military. There are fair arose in the connection with the landing of arms or volunteers, the troops being attached by the mob as they return to the city after trying to intercept them. The troops fired and three persons were killed</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 29th Jul 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Serious news also comes from Eastern Europe after the assassination of the Austrian ground due some weeks ago the origin of the plot was traced to a Belgrade and Austria has on this pretext made certain strong demands since Serbia for apologies etc, Servia gave a favourable reply to the practicality all of these but Austria is nevertheless not satisfied and the war seems probable it seems that Servia will not allow Austrian emissary is to calm and try a subject on our own soil for their complicity in the murder of the Archduke.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">On Tuesday Austria declared war. The outlook seems bad. Russia has declared her </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Friday 31st Jul 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Of contraband leading the Port of London while Mr James Young coming up from Portsmouth says that Portsmouth Harbour has been close our 1st 2nd &amp; 3rd Fleet have put to sea and and troop trains are moving, while the Isle of White packet boats have been commandeered for possible transport duties. At midday we heard here that the stock exchange has been closed indefinitely in the bank rate has gone up to 8%.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">The position is very serious indeed and brings home to one most fably what a defenceless and helpless position one is in without any description of military training. Personally I must confirm that I regret I have not joined the territorial Force before</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">my movements for the week and are made uncertain for even If I do get down to Wellingborough I may have some difficulty in getting back, however tomorrow may bring News one way or the other. I wish I knew where Dorrie was, she was to have left Alexandria on the 25th and was coming home through Italy. She is probably in that country at present but if these mobilising&apos;s move months go on <text:soft-page-break/>she will certainly not be able to come across the continent. Her best place will be back in Egypt&apos;s I should think</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P70">Friday evening we learn that martial law had been reclaimed in Germany but rather reassuring sign was that the Prince Henry of Prussia had gone on a peace mission to St Petersburg</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P73" text:outline-level="4">Wednesday 5th Aug 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Events have moved quickly. We declare war at midnight last night on Germany. She is also at war with France and Russia and Belgium.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">I went down to Wellingborough on sat but could not rest I came back on Monday afternoon looked Kibble up and went to the artists headquarters with him. Nothing doing again last night and was accepted. Recruits join in mobilisation today we are told very certain but good nevertheless. Had told no one bar Danielle of my intentions. Only a hint to Father. We don&apos;t know where where we are going.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Later</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Have been hanging about headquarters all the morning there is a shortage of kit &amp; men rejoining have been given the preference today We are told we will get ours tomorrow. Battalion sleeps at home tonight &amp; probably this arrangement will hold for a week</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 20th Aug 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">the kit above mentioned has not turned up yet. We have done our necessary 40 drills and also some miniature range shooting but are still waiting for the rest of our kit we have bought our own uniforms. I soon settle down again to the Morris tube and got a possible 25 yards.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rifleman.org.uk/Miniature_calibre_adapters_and_conversions.html&quot; title=&quot;Morris Aiming tube&quot;&gt;Morris Aiming tube&lt;/a&gt;</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 21th Aug 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">The Journal this month has come out with the announcement that I won the silver medal and first prize of the city and Guilds examination in brewing</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">nothing particularly eventful as happened in the war No naval engagement has taken place and not big land battles either. The papers have said a lot about Belgian victories but the fact remains that the Germans own front of Namur and are close to Brussels that the government have left it.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_4" text:outline-level="4">Saturday 22th Aug 1914</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">We have no news of Dorrie except that she reached Brindisi Aug 5 &amp; wrote from Venice Aug 10 that they cannot get on &amp; intend to return.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">We have now got all our kit &amp; and will probably join the battalion early next week</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"><text:soft-page-break/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
</office:document>